# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: vertx
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:vertx/event-loop] In software, an **event loop** is an algorithm that continually dispatches control flow for events.
[src:vertx/event-loop] The loop requests the next event from an event provider (which generally blocks the loop until an event occurs), and when an event is received, invokes its associated event handler.
[src:vertx/event-loop] When the event loop is the central event dispatcher of a program, as it often is, it is called the **main loop** or **main event loop**.
[src:vertx/event-loop] In modern environments such as web browsers and server runtimes, the event loop is a fundamental mechanism that enables asynchronous execution by continuously monitoring and dispatching events or messages from a queue when the main program thread is idle.
[src:vertx/event-loop] In JavaScript, the event loop allows non-blocking handling of tasks such as user interactions, timers, and I/O operations despite the language being single-threaded.
[src:vertx/event-loop] The same algorithm can be used to process inbound messages, a superset of events.
[src:vertx/event-loop] In this context, the algorithm is called a **message loop**, **message dispatcher**, or **message pump**.
[src:vertx/event-loop] A common use for a message loop is message passing inter-process communication where the message queue is maintained outside of the program (such as by the operating system).
[src:vertx/event-loop] Typically, a program that operates in a graphical user interface (GUI) environment uses an event loop, and due to the predominance of GUI environments, most modern applications have a main event loop.
[src:vertx/event-loop] In the following pseudocode, `get_next_message()` is a placeholder for a function that is typically provided by the operating system that blocks until a message is available.
[src:vertx/event-loop] Thus, the loop only repeats when there is a message to process.
[src:vertx/event-loop] Many programs include an event loop in the high-level design; a main event loop, but there are alternative designs.
[src:vertx/event-loop] A program can exit as soon as it completes the actions that it's designed to do without external (i.e. user) interaction.
[src:vertx/event-loop] Often, such a program has optional behavior that is set up before the program starts such as via the command-line interface (CLI) or environment variables.
[src:vertx/event-loop] Utility software is often of this nature.
[src:vertx/event-loop] Even if a program provides for user interaction, it might not use an event loop.
[src:vertx/event-loop] A program that provides an internal CLI does include a command processor that is similar to an event loop in that it dispatches to command handlers based on user input.
[src:vertx/event-loop] A web page and its JavaScript typically run in a single-threaded web browser process.
[src:vertx/event-loop] The browser process deals with messages from a queue one at a time.
[src:vertx/event-loop] A JavaScript function or another browser event might be associated with a given message.
[src:vertx/event-loop] When the browser process has finished with a message, it proceeds to the next message in the queue.
[src:vertx/event-loop] In JavaScript environments, the event loop works with separate queues — including a task queue and a microtask queue — to manage asynchronous operations such as timers, promise callbacks, and DOM events.
[src:vertx/event-loop] When the call stack is empty, the event loop selects the next task from these queues to execute.
[src:vertx/event-loop] In Windows, a process that interacts with the user must accept and react to incoming messages, which is almost inevitably done by a message loop in that process.
[src:vertx/event-loop] In Windows, a message is equated to an event created and imposed upon the operating system.
[src:vertx/event-loop] An event can be user interaction, network traffic, system processing, timer activity, inter-process communication, among others.
[src:vertx/event-loop] For non-interactive, I/O only events, Windows has I/O completion ports.
[src:vertx/event-loop] I/O completion port loops run separately from the Message loop, and do not interact with the Message loop out of the box.
[src:vertx/event-loop] The heart of most Win32 applications is the WinMain() function, which calls GetMessage() in a loop.
[src:vertx/event-loop] GetMessage() blocks until a message (event), is received (with function PeekMessage() as a non-blocking alternative).
[src:vertx/event-loop] After some optional processing, it will call DispatchMessage(), which dispatches the message to the relevant handler, also known as WindowProc.
[src:vertx/event-loop] Normally, messages that have no special WindowProc() are dispatched to DefWindowProc, the default one.
[src:vertx/event-loop] DispatchMessage() calls the WindowProc of the HWND handle of the message (registered with the RegisterClass() function).
[src:vertx/event-loop] More recent versions of Windows guarantee that messages will be delivered to an application's message loop in the order that they were perceived by the system and its peripherals.
[src:vertx/event-loop] This guarantee is essential when considering the design consequences of multithreaded applications.
[src:vertx/event-loop] However, some messages have different rules, such as messages that are always received last, or messages with a different documented priority.
[src:vertx/event-loop] X applications using Xlib directly are built around the `XNextEvent` family of functions; `XNextEvent` blocks until an event appears on the event queue, whereupon the application processes it appropriately.
[src:vertx/event-loop] The Xlib event loop only handles window system events; applications that need to be able to wait on other files and devices could construct their own event loop from primitives such as `ConnectionNumber`, but in practice tend to use multithreading.
[src:vertx/event-loop] In the more common case, GUI toolkits based on Xlib usually support adding events.
[src:vertx/event-loop] For example, toolkits based on Xt Intrinsics have `XtAppAddInput()` and `XtAppAddTimeout()`.
[src:vertx/event-loop] It is not safe to call Xlib functions from a signal handler, because the X application may have been interrupted in an arbitrary state, e.g. within `XNextEvent`.
[src:vertx/event-loop] See [1] for a solution for X11R5, X11R6 and Xt.
[src:vertx/event-loop] The GLib event loop was originally created for use in GTK but is now used in non-GUI applications as well, such as D-Bus.
[src:vertx/event-loop] The resource polled is the collection of file descriptors the application is interested in; the polling block will be interrupted if a signal arrives or a timeout expires (e.g. if the application has specified a timeout or idle task).
[src:vertx/event-loop] Application libraries that are built on the GLib event loop include GStreamer and the asynchronous I/O methods of GnomeVFS, but GTK remains the most visible client library.
[src:vertx/event-loop] Events from the windowing system (in X, read off the X socket) are translated by GDK into GTK events and emitted as GLib signals on the application's widget objects.
[src:vertx/event-loop] Exactly one CFRunLoop is allowed per thread, and arbitrarily many sources and observers can be attached.
[src:vertx/event-loop] Sources then communicate with observers through the run loop, with it organising queueing and dispatch of messages.
[src:vertx/event-loop] The CFRunLoop is abstracted in Cocoa as an NSRunLoop, which allows any message (equivalent to a function call in non-reflective runtimes) to be queued for dispatch to any object.
[src:vertx/event-loop] In Unix, the everything is a file paradigm leads to a file-based event loop.
[src:vertx/event-loop] Reading from and writing to files, inter-process communication, network communication, and device control are all achieved using file I/O, with the target identified by a file descriptor.
[src:vertx/event-loop] The select and poll system calls allow a set of file descriptors to be monitored for a change of state, e.g. when data becomes available to be read.
[src:vertx/event-loop] In Unix, a signal is an asynchronous event that is handled by a signal handler which runs while the rest of the task is suspended.
[src:vertx/event-loop] If a signal is received and handled while the task is blocking in `select()`, select will return early with EINTR; if a signal is received while the task is CPU bound, the task will be suspended between instructions until the signal handler returns.
[src:vertx/event-loop] A way to handle a signal is for signal handlers to set a global flag and have the event loop check for the flag immediately before and after the `select()` call; if it is set, handle the signal in the same manner as with events on file descriptors.
[src:vertx/event-loop] Unfortunately, this gives rise to a race condition: if a signal arrives immediately between checking the flag and calling `select()`, it will not be handled until `select()` returns for some other reason (for example, being interrupted by a frustrated user).
[src:vertx/event-loop] The solution arrived at by POSIX is the `pselect()` call, which is similar to `select()` but takes an additional `sigmask` parameter, which describes a *signal mask*.
[src:vertx/event-loop] This allows an application to mask signals in the main task, then remove the mask for the duration of the `select()` call such that signal handlers are only called while the application is I/O bound.
[src:vertx/event-loop] However, implementations of `pselect()` have not always been reliable; versions of Linux prior to 2.6.16 do not have a `pselect()` system call, forcing glibc to emulate it via a method prone to the very same race condition `pselect()` is intended to avoid.
[src:vertx/event-loop] An alternative, more portable solution, is to convert asynchronous events to file-based events using the *self-pipe trick*, where "a signal handler writes a byte to a pipe whose other end is monitored by `select()` in the main program".
[src:vertx/event-loop] In Linux kernel version 2.6.22, a new system call `signalfd()` was added, which allows receiving signals via a special file descriptor.
[src:vertx/event-loop] In environments such as web browsers and Node.js, the event loop is central to asynchronous program behavior.
[src:vertx/event-loop] JavaScript runs on a single thread for execution, but host environments provide APIs for non-blocking operations, such as timers, network requests, and user events.
[src:vertx/event-loop] Completed asynchronous operations are placed in queues, and the event loop repeatedly checks whether the call stack is empty to schedule queued callbacks.
[src:vertx/event-loop] This enables JavaScript applications to remain responsive while handling multiple asynchronous tasks.
[src:vertx/non-blocking-i-o-java] The APIs of NIO were designed to provide access to the low-level I/O operations of modern operating systems.
[src:vertx/non-blocking-i-o-java] Although the APIs are themselves relatively high-level, the intent is to facilitate an implementation that can directly use the most efficient operations of the underlying platform.
[src:vertx/non-blocking-i-o-java] The Java NIO APIs are provided in the `java.nio` package and its subpackages.
[src:vertx/non-blocking-i-o-java] The documentation by Oracle identifies these features.
[src:vertx/non-blocking-i-o-java] NIO data transfer is based on buffers (`java.nio.Buffer` and related classes).
[src:vertx/non-blocking-i-o-java] These classes represent a contiguous extent of memory, together with a small number of data transfer operations.
[src:vertx/non-blocking-i-o-java] Although theoretically these are general-purpose data structures, the implementation may select memory for alignment or paging characteristics, which are not otherwise accessible in Java.
[src:vertx/non-blocking-i-o-java] Typically, this would be used to allow the buffer contents to occupy the same physical memory used by the underlying operating system for its native I/O operations, thus allowing the most direct transfer mechanism, and eliminating the need for any additional copying.
[src:vertx/non-blocking-i-o-java] In most operating systems, provided the particular area of memory has the right properties, transfer can take place without using the CPU at all.
[src:vertx/non-blocking-i-o-java] The NIO buffer is intentionally limited in features in order to support these goals.
[src:vertx/non-blocking-i-o-java] There are buffer classes for all of Java's primitive types except `boolean`, which can share memory with byte buffers and allow arbitrary interpretation of the underlying bytes.
[src:vertx/non-blocking-i-o-java] NIO buffers maintain several pointers that dictate the function of their accessor methods.
[src:vertx/non-blocking-i-o-java] Channels (classes implementing the interface `java.nio.channels.Channel`) are designed to provide for bulk data transfers to and from NIO buffers.
[src:vertx/non-blocking-i-o-java] This is a low-level data transfer mechanism that exists in parallel with the classes of the higher-level I/O library (packages `java.io` and `java.net`).
[src:vertx/non-blocking-i-o-java] A channel implementation can be obtained from a high-level data transfer class such as `java.io.File`, `java.net.ServerSocket`, or `java.net.Socket`, and vice versa.
[src:vertx/non-blocking-i-o-java] Channels are analogous to "file descriptors" found in Unix-like operating systems.
[src:vertx/non-blocking-i-o-java] File channels (`java.nio.channels.FileChannel`) can use arbitrary buffers but can also establish a buffer directly mapped to file contents using memory-mapped file.
[src:vertx/non-blocking-i-o-java] They can also interact with file system locks.
[src:vertx/non-blocking-i-o-java] Similarly, socket channels (`java.nio.channels.SocketChannel` and `java.nio.channels.ServerSocketChannel`) allow for data transfer between sockets and NIO buffers.
[src:vertx/non-blocking-i-o-java] `FileChannel` can be used to do a file copy, which is potentially far more efficient than using old read/write with a byte array.
[src:vertx/non-blocking-i-o-java] A selector (`java.nio.channels.Selector` and subclasses) provides a mechanism for waiting on channels and recognizing when one or more become available for data transfer.
[src:vertx/non-blocking-i-o-java] When a number of channels are registered with the selector, it enables blocking of the program flow until at least one channel is ready for use, or until an interruption condition occurs.
[src:vertx/non-blocking-i-o-java] Although this multiplexing behavior could be implemented with threads, the selector can provide a significantly more efficient implementation using lower-level operating system constructs.
[src:vertx/non-blocking-i-o-java] A POSIX-compliant operating system, for example, would have direct representations of these concepts, select().
[src:vertx/non-blocking-i-o-java] A notable application of this design would be the common paradigm in server software which involves simultaneously waiting for responses on a number of sessions.
[src:vertx/non-blocking-i-o-java] In Java, a character set is a mapping between Unicode characters (or a subset of them) and bytes.
[src:vertx/non-blocking-i-o-java] The `java.nio.charset` package of NIO provides facilities for identifying character sets and providing encoding and decoding algorithms for new mappings.
[src:vertx/non-blocking-i-o-java] It is unexpected that a `java.nio.channels.Channel` associated with a `java.io.RandomAccessFile` closes the file descriptor on an interrupt, whereas `java.io.RandomAccessFile`s' associated `java.nio.channels.FileChannel` does do this.
[src:vertx/non-blocking-i-o-java] JDK 7 includes a `java.nio.file` package which, with the `Path` class (also new to JDK 7), among other features, provides extended capabilities for filesystem tasks, e.g. can work with symbolic/hard links and dump big directory listings into buffers more quickly than the old File class does.
[src:vertx/non-blocking-i-o-java] The `java.nio.file` package and its related package, `java.nio.file.attribute`, provide comprehensive support for file I/O and for accessing the file system.
[src:vertx/non-blocking-i-o-java] A zip file system provider is also available in JDK 7.
[src:vertx/non-blocking-i-o-java] The `java.nio.file.LinkOption` is an example of emulating extensible enums with interfaces.
[src:vertx/non-blocking-i-o-java] In Java, it is not possible to have one `java.lang.Enum` extend another `Enum`.
[src:vertx/non-blocking-i-o-java] However, it is possible to emulate an extensible `Enum` type by having an `Enum` implement one or more interfaces.
[src:vertx/non-blocking-i-o-java] `LinkOption` is an enum type that implements both the `java.nio.file.OpenOption` and `java.nio.file.CopyOption` interfaces, which emulates the effects of an extensible `Enum` type.
[src:vertx/non-blocking-i-o-java] A small down-side to this approach is that implementations cannot be inherited between various `Enum` types.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] In computing, **reactive programming** is a declarative programming paradigm concerned with data streams and the propagation of change.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] With this paradigm, it is possible to express static (e.g., arrays) or dynamic (e.g., event emitters) data streams with ease, and also communicate that an inferred dependency within the associated execution model exists, which facilitates the automatic propagation of the changed data flow.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] For example, in *imperative* programming, `a := b + c` would mean that `a` is being assigned the result of `b + c` at the time the expression is evaluated, and later, the values of `b` and `c` can be changed with no effect on the value of `a`.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] In contrast, in *reactive* programming, the value of `a` is automatically updated whenever the values of `b` or `c` change, without the program having to explicitly re-state the statement `a := b + c` to re-assign the value of `a`.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Another example is a hardware description language such as Verilog, where reactive programming enables changes to be modeled as they propagate through circuits.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Reactive programming has been proposed as a way to simplify creating interactive user interfaces and near-real-time computing animation.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] For example, in a model–view–controller (MVC) architecture, reactive programming can facilitate changes in an underlying *model* being reflected automatically in an associated *view*.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Several popular approaches are employed in creating reactive programming languages.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] One approach is the specification of *dedicated* languages that are specific to various *domain constraints*.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Such constraints usually are characterized by real-time, embedded computing or hardware description.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Another approach involves the specification of *general-purpose* languages that include support for reactivity.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Other approaches are articulated in the definition, and use of programming *libraries*, or *embedded domain-specific languages*, that enable reactivity alongside or atop a programming language.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Specification and use of these different approaches results in language *capability trade-offs*.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] In general, the more restricted a language is, the more its associated compilers and analysis programming tools are able to inform developers (e.g., in performing analysis for whether programs are able to execute in actual real-time).
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Functional trade-offs in specificity may result in deterioration of the general applicability of a language.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] A variety of models and semantics govern reactive programming.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Reactive programming language runtimes are represented by a graph that identifies the dependencies among the involved reactive values.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] In such a graph, *nodes* represent the act of computing, and *edges* model dependency relationships.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Such a runtime employs said graph, to help it keep track of the various computations, which must be executed anew, once an involved input changes value.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] At the implementation level, *event reaction* consists of the propagation across a graph's information, which characterizes the existence of change.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Consequently, computations that are affected by such change then become outdated and must be flagged for re-execution.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Such computations are then usually characterized by the transitive closure of the change (i.e., the full set of transitive dependencies a source affects) in its associated source.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] *Change propagation* may then lead to an update in the value of the graph's *sinks*.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Graph propagated information can consist of a node's complete state, i.e., the computation result of the involved node.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] In such cases, the node's previous output is then ignored.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Another method involves *delta propagation* i.e.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] In this case, information is proliferated along a graph's *edges,* which consist only of *delta*s describing how the previous node was changed.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] This approach is especially important when *nodes* hold large amounts of *state data*, which would otherwise be expensive to recompute from scratch.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Another common optimization is employment of *unary change accumulation* and *batch propagation*.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Such a solution can be faster because it reduces communication among involved nodes.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Optimization strategies can then be employed that reason about the nature of the changes contained within, and make alterations accordingly (e.g. two changes in the batch can cancel each other, and thus, simply be ignored).
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Yet another available approach, is described as *invalidity notification propagation*.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] This approach causes nodes with invalid input to pull updates, thus resulting in the update of their own outputs.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] A graph of dependencies is program-specific and generated by a programmer.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] When propagating changes, it is possible to pick propagation orders such that the value of an expression is not a natural consequence of the source program.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] We can illustrate this easily with an example.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Suppose `seconds` is a reactive value that changes every second to represent the current time (in seconds).
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Because `t` should always be greater than `seconds`, this expression should always evaluate to a true value.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Unfortunately, this can depend on the order of evaluation.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] When `seconds` changes, two expressions have to update: `seconds + 1` and the conditional.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] If the first evaluates before the second, then this invariant will hold.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] If, however, the conditional updates first, using the old value of `t` and the new value of `seconds`, then the expression will evaluate to a false value.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Some reactive languages are glitch-free and prove this property.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] This is usually achieved by topologically sorting expressions and updating values in topological order.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] This can, however, have performance implications, such as delaying the delivery of values (due to the order of propagation).
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Topological sorting of dependencies depends on the dependency graph being a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] In practice, a program may define a dependency graph that has cycles.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Usually, reactive programming languages expect such cycles to be "broken" by placing some element along a "back edge" to permit reactive updating to terminate.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Typically, languages provide an operator like `delay` that is used by the update mechanism for this purpose, since a `delay` implies that what follows must be evaluated in the "next time step" (allowing the current evaluation to terminate).
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Reactive languages typically assume that their expressions are purely functional.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] This allows an update mechanism to choose different orders in which to perform updates, and leave the specific order unspecified (thereby enabling optimizations).
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] When a reactive language is embedded in a programming language with state, however, it may be possible for programmers to perform mutable operations.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] How to make this interaction smooth remains an open problem.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] In some cases, it is possible to have principled partial solutions.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] In some reactive languages, the graph of dependencies is *static*, i.e., the graph is fixed throughout a program's execution.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] In other languages, the graph can be *dynamic*, i.e., it can change as the program executes.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Every second, the value of this expression changes to a different reactive expression, which `t + 1` then depends on.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Therefore, the graph of dependencies updates every second.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Permitting dynamic updating of dependencies provides significant expressive power (for instance, dynamic dependencies routinely occur in graphical user interface (GUI) programs).
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] However, the reactive update engine must decide whether to reconstruct expressions each time, or to keep an expression's node constructed but inactive; in the latter case, ensure that they do not participate in the computation when they are not supposed to be active.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Reactive programming languages can range from very explicit ones where data flows are set up by using arrows, to implicit where the data flows are derived from language constructs that look similar to those of imperative or functional programming.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] For example, in an implicitly lifted functional reactive programming (FRP), a function call might implicitly cause a node in a data flow graph to be constructed.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Reactive programming libraries for dynamic languages (such as the Lisp "Cells" and Python "Trellis" libraries) can construct a dependency graph from runtime analysis of the values read during a function's execution, allowing data flow specifications to be both implicit and dynamic.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Sometimes the term *reactive programming* refers to the architectural level of software engineering, where individual nodes in the data flow graph are ordinary programs that communicate with each other.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Reactive programming can be purely static where the data flows are set up statically, or be dynamic where the data flows can change during the execution of a program.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] The use of data switches in the data flow graph could to some extent make a static data flow graph appear as dynamic, and blur the distinction slightly.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] True dynamic reactive programming however could use imperative programming to reconstruct the data flow graph.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Reactive programming could be said to be of **higher order** if it supports the idea that data flows could be used to construct other data flows.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] That is, the resulting value out of a data flow is another data flow graph that is executed using the same evaluation model as the first.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Ideally all data changes are propagated instantly, but this cannot be assured in practice.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Instead, it might be necessary to give different parts of the data flow graph different evaluation priorities.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] This can be called **differentiated reactive programming**.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] For example, in a word processor, marking spelling errors need not be synchronized fully with adding or inserting characters.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Here, differentiated reactive programming can be used to give a spell checker lower priority, allowing it to be delayed while keeping other data flows more immediate.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] However, such differentiation introduces added design complexity.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] For example, deciding how to define the different data flow areas, and how to handle event passing between different data flow areas.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Evaluation of reactive programs is not necessarily based on how stack-based programming languages are evaluated.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Instead, when some data is changed, the change is propagated to all data that is derived partially or completely from the data that was changed.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] This change propagation could be achieved in a number of ways, where perhaps the most natural way is an invalidate/lazy-revalidate scheme.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] It could be problematic simply to naively propagate a change using a stack, because of potential exponential update complexity if the data structure has a certain shape.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] One such shape can be described as "repeated diamonds shape", and has the following structure: An→Bn→An+1, An→Cn→An+1, where n=1,2...
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] This problem could be overcome by propagating invalidation only when some data is not already invalidated, and later re-validate the data when needed using lazy evaluation.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] One inherent problem for reactive programming is that most computations that would be evaluated and forgotten in a normal programming language, needs to be represented in the memory as data-structures.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] This could potentially make reactive programming highly memory consuming.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] However, research on what is called *lowering* could potentially overcome this problem.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] On the other side, reactive programming is a form of what could be described as "explicit parallelism", and could therefore be beneficial for using the power of parallel hardware.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Reactive programming has principal similarities with the observer pattern commonly used in object-oriented programming.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] However, integrating the data flow concepts into the programming language would make it easier to express them and could therefore increase the granularity of the data flow graph.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] For example, the observer pattern commonly describes data flows between whole objects/classes, whereas object-oriented reactive programming could target the members of objects/classes.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] It is possible to fuse reactive programming with ordinary imperative programming.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] In such a paradigm, imperative programs operate upon reactive data structures.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Such a set-up is analogous to imperative constraint programming; however, while imperative constraint programming manages bidirectional data-flow constraints, imperative reactive programming manages one-way data-flow constraints.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] One reference implementation is the proposed Quantum runtime extension to JavaScript.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Object-oriented reactive programming (OORP) is a combination of object-oriented programming and reactive programming.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Perhaps the most natural way to make such a combination is this: instead of methods and fields, objects have *reactions* that automatically re-evaluate when the other reactions they depend on have been modified.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] If an OORP language maintains its imperative methods, it would also fall under the category of imperative reactive programming.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Functional reactive programming (FRP) is a programming paradigm for reactive programming on functional programming.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] The actor model (actors) is proposed to design reactive systems, often combined with functional reactive programming (FRP) and Reactive Streams to develop distributed reactive systems.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] A newer category of programming languages uses constraints (rules) as main programming concept.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] It consists of reactions to events, which keep all constraints satisfied.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] Not only does this facilitate event-based reactions, but it makes reactive programs instrumental to the correctness of software.
[src:vertx/reactive-programming] An example of a rule based reactive programming language is Ampersand, which is founded in relation algebra.
[src:vertx/vert-x] Similar environments written in other programming languages include Node.js for JavaScript, Twisted for Python, Perl Object Environment for Perl, libevent for C, reactPHP and amphp for PHP and EventMachine for Ruby.
[src:vertx/vert-x] Vert.x was started by Tim Fox in 2011 while he was employed by VMware.
[src:vertx/vert-x] Fox initially named the project "Node.x", a play on the naming of Node.js, with the "x" representing the fact that the new project was polyglot in nature, and didn't simply support JavaScript.
[src:vertx/vert-x] The project was later renamed to "Vert.x" to avoid any potential legal issues as "Node" was a trademark owned by Joyent Inc.
[src:vertx/vert-x] The new name was also a play on the name node, as a vertex is a synonym for a node in mathematics.
[src:vertx/vert-x] After much discussion with other parties, in January 2013, VMware was persuaded that it would be in the best interests of the Vert.x community to move the project and associated IP to the Eclipse Foundation, a neutral legal entity.
[src:vertx/vert-x] In August 2013, the core Vert.x project completed its move to the Eclipse Foundation.
[src:vertx/vert-x] The other projects that make up the Vert.x stack did not migrate to Eclipse but continued to use the "Vert.x" trademark with tacit approval of the Eclipse Foundation.
[src:vertx/vert-x] In May 2014, Vert.x won the award for "Most Innovative Java Technology" at the JAX Innovation awards.
[src:vertx/vert-x] On January 12, 2016, Tim Fox stepped down as the lead of the Vert.x project. and Julien Viet, a long-time contributor, took his place.
[src:vertx/vert-x] Both cases will result in a web server serving content in a highly scalable manner.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] The functionality in core is fairly low level - you won’t find stuff like database access, authorisation or high level web functionality here - that kind of stuff you’ll find in **Vert.x ext** (extensions).
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] It’s also entirely embeddable in your existing applications - we don’t force you to structure your applications in a special way just so you can use Vert.x.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] You can use core from any of the other languages that Vert.x supports.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] But here’s a cool bit - we don’t force you to use the Java API directly from, say, JavaScript or Ruby - after all, different languages have different conventions and idioms, and it would be odd to force Java idioms on Ruby developers (for example).
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Instead, we automatically generate an **idiomatic** equivalent of the core Java APIs for each language.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] From now on we’ll just use the word **core** to refer to Vert.x core.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Let’s discuss the different concepts and features in core.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] You can’t do much in Vert.x-land unless you can communicate with a `Vertx` object!
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] It’s the control centre of Vert.x and is how you do pretty much everything, including creating clients and servers, getting a reference to the event bus, setting timers, as well as many other things.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] The `VertxOptions` object has many settings and allows you to configure things like clustering, high availability, pool sizes and various other settings.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] If you’re creating a **clustered Vert.x** (See the section on the event bus for more information on clustering the event bus), then you will normally use the asynchronous variant to create the Vertx object.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] This is because it usually takes some time (maybe a few seconds) for the different Vert.x instances in a cluster to group together.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] During that time, we don’t want to block the calling thread, so we give the result to you asynchronously.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] You may have noticed that in the previous examples a **fluent** API was used.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] A fluent API is where multiple methods calls can be chained together.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] This is a common pattern throughout Vert.x APIs, so get used to it.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Chaining calls like this allows you to write code that’s a little bit less verbose.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] The Vert.x APIs are largely *event driven*.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] This means that when things happen in Vert.x that you are interested in, Vert.x will call you by sending you events.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] You handle events by providing *handlers* to the Vert.x APIs.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Some time later when Vert.x has an event to pass to your handler Vert.x will call it **asynchronously**.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] With very few exceptions (i.e. some file system operations ending in 'Sync'), none of the APIs in Vert.x block the calling thread.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] If a result can be provided immediately, it will be returned immediately, otherwise you will usually provide a handler to receive events some time later.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Because none of the Vert.x APIs block threads that means you can use Vert.x to handle a lot of concurrency using just a small number of threads.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] In all the above cases, when your thread is waiting for a result it can’t do anything else - it’s effectively useless.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] This means that if you want a lot of concurrency using blocking APIs then you need a lot of threads to prevent your application grinding to a halt.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Threads have overhead in terms of the memory they require (e.g. for their stack) and in context switching.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] For the levels of concurrency required in many modern applications, a blocking approach just doesn’t scale.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] We mentioned before that Vert.x APIs are event driven - Vert.x passes events to handlers when they are available.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] In most cases Vert.x calls your handlers using a thread called an **event loop**.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] As nothing in Vert.x or your application blocks, the event loop can merrily run around delivering events to different handlers in succession as they arrive.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Because nothing blocks, an event loop can potentially deliver huge amounts of events in a short amount of time.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] For example a single event loop can handle many thousands of HTTP requests very quickly.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] You may have heard of this before - for example Node.js implements this pattern.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] In a standard reactor implementation there is a **single event loop** thread which runs around in a loop delivering all events to all handlers as they arrive.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] The trouble with a single thread is it can only run on a single core at any one time, so if you want your single threaded reactor application (e.g. your Node.js application) to scale over your multi-core server you have to start up and manage many different processes.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Instead of a single event loop, each Vertx instance maintains **several event loops**.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] By default we choose the number based on the number of available cores on the machine, but this can be overridden.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] This means a single Vertx process can scale across your server, unlike Node.js.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] We call this pattern the **Multi-Reactor Pattern** to distinguish it from the single threaded reactor pattern.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] We already know that the Vert.x APIs are non blocking and won’t block the event loop, but that’s not much help if you block the event loop **yourself** in a handler.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] If you do that, then that event loop will not be able to do anything else while it’s blocked.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] If you block all of the event loops in Vertx instance then your application will grind to a complete halt!
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] If any of the above stop the event loop from doing anything else for a **significant amount of time** then you should go immediately to the naughty step, and await further instructions.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] So… what is a **significant amount of time**?
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] It really depends on your application and the amount of concurrency you require.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] If you have a single event loop, and you want to handle 10000 http requests per second, then it’s clear that each request can’t take more than 0.1 ms to process, so you can’t block for any more time than that.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] If your application is not responsive it might be a sign that you are blocking an event loop somewhere.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] To help you diagnose such issues, Vert.x will automatically log warnings if it detects an event loop hasn’t returned for some time.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] If you see warnings like these in your logs, then you should investigate.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Vert.x will also provide stack traces to pinpoint exactly where the blocking is occurring.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] If you want to turn off these warnings or change the settings, you can do that in the `VertxOptions` object before creating the Vertx object.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Vert.x 4 use futures to represent asynchronous results.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Any asynchronous method returns a `Future` object for the result of the call: a *success* or a *failure*.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] You cannot interact directly with the result of a future, instead you need to set a handler that will be called when the future completes and the result is available, like any other kind of event.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] When these 3 steps are successful, the final future (`future`) will succeed.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] However, if one of the steps fails, the final future will fail.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Coordination of multiple futures can be achieved with Vert.x `futures`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] It supports concurrent composition (run several async operations in parallel) and sequential composition (chain async operations).
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] The operations run concurrently, the `Handler` attached to the returned future is invoked upon completion of the composition.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] When one of the operation fails (one of the passed future is marked as a failure), the resulting future is marked as failed too.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] When all the operations succeed, the resulting future is completed with a success.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] On success, the `resultAt` method guarantees the results in the same order specified in the call to `Future.all`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] In the example above, regardless of which item completed first, the `httpServer` result can be accessed using `resultAt(0)` and the `netServer` result can be accessed using `resultAt(1)`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] While the `all` composition *waits* until all futures are successful (or one fails), the `any` composition *waits* for the first succeeded future.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] The `join` composition *waits* until all futures are completed, either with a success or a failure.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] The Vert.x `Future` API offers compatibility *from* and *to* `CompletionStage` which is the JDK interface for composable asynchronous operations.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] We can conversely go from a `CompletionStage` to Vert.x `Future` using `Future.fromCompletionStage`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] 2. the second variant takes an extra `Context` parameter to call the `Future` methods on a Vert.x context.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Vert.x comes with a simple, scalable, *actor-like* deployment and concurrency model out of the box that you can use to save you writing your own.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] The model does not claim to be a strict actor-model implementation, but it does share similarities especially with respect to concurrency, scaling and deployment.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] To use this model, you write your code as set of **verticles**.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Verticles are chunks of code that get deployed and run by Vert.x.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] A Vert.x instance maintains N event loop threads (where N by default is core*2) by default.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Verticles can be written in any of the languages that Vert.x supports and a single application can include verticles written in multiple languages.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] You can think of a verticle as a bit like an actor in the Actor Model.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] An application would typically be composed of many verticle instances running in the same Vert.x instance at the same time.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] The different verticle instances communicate with each other by sending messages on the event bus.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Verticle classes must implement the `Deployable` interface.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] They can implement it directly if you like, but usually it’s simpler to extend the abstract class `VerticleBase`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Normally you would override the start method like in the example above.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] When Vert.x deploys the verticle it will call the start method, and when future returned by the method has completed the verticle will be considered started.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] You can also optionally override the stop method.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] This will be called by Vert.x when the verticle is un-deployed and when the future returned by the method has completed the verticle will be considered stopped.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Nevertheless, `Verticle` and `AbstractVerticle` are not deprecated in Vert.x 5.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] It is fine to use them, however it is not the default recommended choice anymore.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] These are the most common and useful type - they are always executed using an event loop thread.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] We’ll discuss this more in the next section.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] These run using a thread from the worker pool.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] An instance is never executed concurrently by more than one thread.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Standard verticles are assigned an event loop thread when they are created and the start method is called with that event loop.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] When you call any other methods that takes a handler on a core API from an event loop then Vert.x will guarantee that those handlers, when called, will be executed on the same event loop.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] This means we can guarantee that all the code in your verticle instance is always executed on the same event loop (as long as you don’t create your own threads and call it!).
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] This means you can write all the code in your application as single threaded and let Vert.x worry about the threading and scaling.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] No more worrying about synchronized and volatile any more, and you also avoid many other cases of race conditions and deadlock so prevalent when doing hand-rolled 'traditional' multi-threaded application development.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] A worker verticle is just like a standard verticle but it’s executed using a thread from the Vert.x worker thread pool, rather than using an event loop.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Worker verticles are designed for calling blocking code, as they won’t block any event loops.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] If you don’t want to use a worker verticle to run blocking code, you can also run inline blocking code directly while on an event loop.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] If you want to deploy a verticle as a worker verticle you do that with `setThreadingModel`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Worker verticle instances are never executed concurrently by Vert.x by more than one thread, but can executed by different threads at different times.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] A virtual thread verticle is just like a standard verticle but it’s executed using virtual threads, rather than using an event loop.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Virtual thread verticles are designed to use an async/await model with Vert.x futures.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] If you want to deploy a verticle as a virtual thread verticle you do that with `setThreadingModel`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] You can deploy a verticle using one of the `deployVerticle` method, specifying a verticle name, or you can pass in a verticle instance you have already created yourself.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] You can also deploy verticles by specifying the verticle **name**.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] The verticle name is used to look up the specific `VerticleFactory` that will be used to instantiate the actual verticle instance(s).
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] When deploying verticle(s) using a name, the name is used to select the actual verticle factory that will instantiate the verticle(s).
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Verticle names can have a prefix - which is a string followed by a colon, which when present will be used to lookup the factory, e.g.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] When prefix is absent, Vert.x will look for a suffix and use that to lookup the factory, e.g.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] If no prefix or suffix is present, Vert.x will assume it’s a Java fully qualified class name (FQCN) and try and instantiate that.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Most Verticle factories are loaded from the classpath and registered at Vert.x startup.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] You can also programmatically register and unregister verticle factories using `registerVerticleFactory` and `unregisterVerticleFactory` if you wish.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Verticle deployment is asynchronous and may complete some time after the call to deploy has returned.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] The completion handler will be passed a result containing the deployment ID string, if deployment succeeded.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] This deployment ID can be used later if you want to undeploy the deployment.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Deployments can be un-deployed with `undeploy`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] When deploying a verticle using a verticle, you can specify the number of verticle instances that you want to deploy, you also need to pass a `Callable<Deployable>` so Vert.x can instantiate your verticle instances.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] This is useful for scaling easily across multiple cores.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] For example, you might have a web-server verticle to deploy and multiple cores on your machine, so you want to deploy multiple instances to utilise all the cores.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] This configuration is then available via the `Context` object or directly using the `config` method.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Threads maintained by Vert.x instances are not daemon threads so they will prevent the JVM from exiting.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] If you are embedding Vert.x and you have finished with it, you can call `close` to close it down.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] This will shut-down all internal thread pools and close other resources, and will allow the JVM to exit.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] When Vert.x provides an event to a handler or calls the start or stop methods of a `Verticle`, the execution is associated with a `Context`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Usually a context is an **event-loop context** and is tied to a specific event loop thread.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] So executions for that context always occur on that exact same event loop thread.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] In the case of worker verticles and running inline blocking code a worker context will be associated with the execution which will use a thread from the worker thread pool.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] If the current thread has a context associated with it, it reuses the context object.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] If not a new instance of context is created.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] When you have retrieved the context object, you can run code in this context asynchronously.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] When several handlers run in the same context, they may want to share data.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] The context object offers methods to store and retrieve data shared in the context.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] The context object also let you access verticle configuration using the `config` method.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Check the Passing configuration to a verticle section for more details about this configuration.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] It’s very common in Vert.x to want to perform an action after a delay, or periodically.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] In standard verticles you can’t just make the thread sleep to introduce a delay, as that will block the event loop thread.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Timers can be **one-shot** or **periodic**.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] A one shot timer calls an event handler after a certain delay, expressed in milliseconds.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] The return value is a unique timer id which can later be used to cancel the timer.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] The handler is also passed the timer id.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] You can also set a timer to fire periodically by using `setPeriodic`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] There will be an initial delay equal to the period.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] The return value of `setPeriodic` is a unique timer id (long).
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] This can be later used if the timer needs to be cancelled.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Keep in mind that the timer will fire on a periodic basis.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] If your periodic treatment takes a long amount of time to proceed, your timer events could run continuously or even worse : stack up.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] In this case, you should consider using `setTimer` instead.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Once your treatment has finished, you can set the next timer.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] To cancel a periodic timer, call `cancelTimer` specifying the timer id.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] `Timer` combines one-shot timer and in a single API.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] The future succeeds when the timer fires, conversely `cancelling` the timer fails the future.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] If you’re creating timers from inside verticles, those timers will be automatically closed when the verticle is undeployed.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Verticles use the Vert.x worker pool for executing blocking actions, i.e `executeBlocking` or worker verticle.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] The `event bus` is the **nervous system** of Vert.x.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] There is a single event bus instance for every Vert.x instance and it is obtained using the method `eventBus`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] The event bus allows different parts of your application to communicate with each other, irrespective of what language they are written in, and whether they’re in the same Vert.x instance, or in a different Vert.x instance.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] It can even be bridged to allow client-side JavaScript running in a browser to communicate on the same event bus.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] The event bus forms a distributed peer-to-peer messaging system spanning multiple server nodes and multiple browsers.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] The event bus supports publish/subscribe, point-to-point, and request-response messaging.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] It basically involves registering handlers, unregistering handlers and sending and publishing messages.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Messages are sent on the event bus to an **address**.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Vert.x doesn’t bother with any fancy addressing schemes.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] In Vert.x an address is simply a string.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] However, it is wise to use some kind of scheme, *e.g.* using periods to demarcate a namespace.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Some examples of valid addresses are europe.news.feed1, acme.games.pacman, sausages, and X.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Many different handlers can be registered at the same address.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] A single handler can be registered at many different addresses.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] The event bus supports **publishing** messages.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Publishing means delivering the message to all handlers that are registered at that address.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] This is the familiar **publish/subscribe** messaging pattern.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] The event bus also supports **point-to-point** messaging.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Vert.x will then route them to just one of the handlers registered at that address.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] If there is more than one handler registered at the address, one will be chosen using a non-strict round-robin algorithm.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] With point-to-point messaging, an optional reply handler can be specified when sending the message.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] When a message is received by a recipient, and has been handled, the recipient can optionally decide to reply to the message.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] If they do so, the reply handler will be called.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] When the reply is received back by the sender, it too can be replied to.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] This can be repeated *ad infinitum*, and allows a dialog to be set up between two different verticles.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] This is a common messaging pattern called the **request-response** pattern.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Vert.x does its best to deliver messages and won’t consciously throw them away.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] This is called **best-effort** delivery.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] However, in case of failure of all or parts of the event bus, there is a possibility messages might be lost.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] If your application cares about lost messages, you should code your handlers to be idempotent, and your senders to retry after recovery.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Out of the box Vert.x allows any primitive/simple type, String, or `buffers` to be sent as messages.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] JSON is very easy to create, read and parse in all the languages that Vert.x supports, so it has become a kind of *lingua franca* for Vert.x.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] However, you are not forced to use JSON if you don’t want to.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] The event bus is very flexible and also supports sending arbitrary objects over the event bus.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] You can do this by defining a `codec` for the objects you want to send.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] There is a single instance of the event bus per Vert.x instance.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] This simplest way to register a handler is using `consumer`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] When a message arrives for your handler, your handler will be called, passing in the `message`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] The object returned from call to consumer() is an instance of `MessageConsumer`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] This object can subsequently be used to unregister the handler, or use the handler as a stream.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Alternatively you can use `consumer` to return a MessageConsumer with no handler set, and then set the handler on that.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] When registering a handler on a clustered event bus, it can take some time for the registration to reach all nodes of the cluster.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] If you want to be notified when this has completed, you can use the `completion future` on the MessageConsumer object.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] To unregister a handler, call `unregister`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] If you are on a clustered event bus, un-registering can take some time to propagate across the nodes.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] If you want to be notified when this is complete, use the future returned by `unregister`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Just use `publish` specifying the address to publish it to.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] That message will then be delivered to all handlers registered against the address news.uk.sport.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Sending a message will result in only one handler registered at the address receiving the message.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] This is the point-to-point messaging pattern.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] The handler is chosen in a non-strict round-robin fashion.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Messages sent over the event bus can also contain headers.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Vert.x will deliver messages to any particular handler in the same order they were sent from any particular sender.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] The object you receive in a message handler is a `Message`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] The `body` of the message corresponds to the object that was sent or published.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] The headers of the message are available with `headers`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] When using `send` the event bus attempts to deliver the message to a `MessageConsumer` registered with the event bus.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] In some cases it’s useful for the sender to know when the consumer has received the message and "processed" it using **request-response** pattern.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] To acknowledge that the message has been processed, the consumer can reply to the message by calling `reply`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] When this happens it causes a reply to be sent back to the sender and the reply handler is invoked with the reply.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] The reply can contain a message body which can contain useful information.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] What the "processing" actually means is application-defined and depends entirely on what the message consumer does and is not something that the Vert.x event bus itself knows or cares about.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] When sending a message with a reply handler, you can specify a timeout in the `DeliveryOptions`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] If a reply is not received within that time, the reply handler will be called with a failure.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] In all cases, the reply handler will be called with the specific failure.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] You can send any object you like across the event bus if you define and register a `message codec` for it.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] You unregister a message codec with `unregisterCodec`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Message codecs don’t always have to encode and decode as the same type.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] For example you can write a codec that allows a MyPOJO class to be sent, but when that message is sent to a handler it arrives as a MyOtherPOJO class.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] The event bus doesn’t just exist in a single Vert.x instance.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] By clustering different Vert.x instances together on your network they can form a single, distributed event bus.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] You should also make sure you have one of the `ClusterManager` implementations on your classpath.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] If you’re registering event bus handlers from inside verticles, those handlers will be automatically unregistered when the verticle is undeployed.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] The event bus can be configured.It is particularly useful when the event bus is clustered.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] Under the hood the event bus uses TCP connections to send and receive messages, so the `EventBusOptions` let you configure all aspects of these TCP connections.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] As the event bus acts as a server and client, the configuration is close to `NetClientOptions` and `NetServerOptions`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] The previous snippet depicts how you can use SSL connections for the event bus, instead of plain TCP connections.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] The event bus configuration needs to be consistent in all the cluster nodes.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p01] The `EventBusOptions` also lets you specify whether the event bus is clustered, the port and host.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] Unlike some other languages, Java does not have first class support for JSON so we provide two classes to make handling JSON in your Vert.x applications a bit easier.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] The `JsonObject` class represents JSON objects.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] A JSON object is basically just a map which has string keys and values can be of one of the JSON supported types (string, number, boolean).
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] Empty JSON objects can be created with the default constructor.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] Use the `put` methods to put values into the JSON object.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] Note that both of the above mapping directions use Jackson’s `ObjectMapper#convertValue()` to perform the mapping.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] See the Jackson documentation for information on the impact of field and constructor visibility, caveats on serialization and deserialization across object references, etc.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] However, in the simplest case, both `mapFrom` and `mapTo` should succeed if all fields of the Java class are public (or have public getters/setters), and if there is a public default constructor (or no defined constructors).
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] Referenced objects will be transitively serialized/deserialized to/from nested JSON objects as long as the object graph is acyclic.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] You use `encode` to encode the object to a String form.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] The `JsonArray` class represents JSON arrays.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] A JSON array is a sequence of values (string, number, boolean).
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] JSON arrays can also contain null values.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] Empty JSON arrays can be created with the default constructor.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] You add entries to a JSON array using the `add` methods.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] You use `encode` to encode the array to a String form.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] Creating JSON object and array assumes you are using valid string representation.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] `JsonObject` / JsonArray`encoding and decoding is backed by the Jackson library, `Json static methods uses it as well.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] Since Jackson 2.15, upper bound constraints have been added to limit the bytes cumulated when parsing a JSON input.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] You can refer to this for more information.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] Jackson Databind extension is supported, powering JSON/Object mapping facilities such as `mapTo` or `Json.encode`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] By choice, Jackson Databind is not a dependency of `io.vertx:vertx-core`, it should be explicitly as a dependency of your project.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] Vert.x provides an implementation of Json Pointers from RFC6901.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] You can use pointers both for querying and for writing.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] After instantiating your pointer, use `queryJson` to query a JSON value.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] Most data is shuffled around inside Vert.x using buffers.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] A buffer is a sequence of zero or more bytes that can read from or written to and which expands automatically as necessary to accommodate any bytes written to it.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] You can perhaps think of a buffer as smart byte array.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] Buffers can create by using one of the static `Buffer.buffer` methods.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] Buffers can be initialised from strings or byte arrays, or empty buffers can be created.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] The String will be encoded in the buffer using UTF-8.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] Create a buffer with an initial size hint.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] If you know your buffer will have a certain amount of data written to it you can create the buffer and specify this size.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] This makes the buffer initially allocate that much memory and is more efficient than the buffer automatically resizing multiple times as data is written to it.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] Note that buffers created this way **are empty**.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] It does not create a buffer filled with zeros up to the specified size.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] There are two ways to write to a buffer: appending, and random access.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] In either case buffers will always expand automatically to encompass the bytes.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] It’s not possible to get an `IndexOutOfBoundsException` with a buffer.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] To append to a buffer, you use the `appendXXX` methods.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] Append methods exist for appending various different types.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] You can also write into the buffer at a specific index, by using the `setXXX` methods.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] Set methods exist for various different data types.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] All the set methods take an index as the first argument - this represents the position in the buffer where to start writing the data.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] The buffer will always expand as necessary to accommodate the data.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] Data is read from a buffer using the `getXXX` methods.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] Get methods exist for various datatypes.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] The first argument to these methods is an index in the buffer from where to get the data.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] Unsigned numbers can be read from or appended/set to a buffer with the `getUnsignedXXX`, `appendUnsignedXXX` and `setUnsignedXXX` methods.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] This is useful when implementing a codec for a network protocol optimized to minimize bandwidth consumption.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] Use `length` to obtain the length of the buffer.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] The length of a buffer is the index of the byte in the buffer with the largest index + 1.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] A sliced buffer is a new buffer which backs onto the original buffer, i.e. it does not copy the underlying data.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] After writing a buffer to a socket or other similar place, they cannot be re-used.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] Vert.x allows you to easily write non-blocking TCP clients and servers.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] To tell the server to listen for incoming requests you use one of the `listen` alternatives.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] The default host is `0.0.0.0` which means 'listen on all available addresses' and the default port is `0`, which is a special value that instructs the server to find a random unused local port and use that.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] The actual bind is asynchronous, so the server might not actually be listening until some time **after** the call to listen has returned.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] If you want to be notified when the server is actually listening you can provide a handler to the `listen` call.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] If `0` is used as the listening port, the server will find an unused random port to listen on.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] To find out the real port the server is listening on you can call `actualPort`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] When a connection is made the handler will be called with an instance of `NetSocket`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] This is a socket-like interface to the actual connection, and allows you to read and write data as well as do various other things like close the socket.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] To read data from the socket you set the `handler` on the socket.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] This handler will be called with an instance of `Buffer` every time data is received on the socket.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] You write to a socket using one of `write`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] Write operations are asynchronous and may not occur until some time after the call to write has returned.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] You can set an `exceptionHandler` to receive any exceptions that happen on the socket.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] You can set an `exceptionHandler` to receive any exceptions that happens before the connection is passed to the `connectHandler` , e.g during the TLS handshake.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] The local address of a `NetSocket` can be retrieved using `localAddress`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] The remote address, (i.e. the address of the other end of the connection) of a `NetSocket` can be retrieved using `remoteAddress`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] Files and classpath resources can be written to the socket directly using `sendFile`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] This can be a very efficient way to send files, as it can be handled by the OS kernel directly where supported by the operating system.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] Please see the chapter about serving files from the classpath for restrictions of the classpath resolution or disabling it.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] Instances of `NetSocket` are also `ReadStream` and `WriteStream` instances, so they can be used to pipe data to or from other read and write streams.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] See the chapter on streams for more information.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] You can shut down a `server` or `client`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] Calling `shutdown` initiates the shut-down phase whereby the server or client are given the opportunity to perform clean-up actions and handle shutdown at the protocol level.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] Shut-down waits until all sockets are closed or the shut-down timeout fires.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] When the timeout fires, all sockets are forcibly closed.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] Each opened socket is notified with a shutdown event, allowing to perform a protocol level close before the actual socket close.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] You can close a `server` or `client` to immediately close all open connections and releases all resources.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] Unlike `shutdown` there is not grace period.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] The close is actually asynchronous and might not complete until some time after the call has returned.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] You can use the returned future to be notified when the actual close has completed.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] This future is completed when the close has fully completed.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] If you’re creating TCP servers and clients from inside verticles, those servers and clients will be automatically closed when the verticle is undeployed.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] The handlers of any TCP server are always executed on the same event loop thread.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] This means that if you are running on a server with a lot of cores, and you only have this one instance deployed then you will have at most one core utilised on your server.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] In order to utilise more cores of your server you will need to deploy more instances of the server.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] Once you do this you will find the echo server works functionally identically to before, but all your cores on your server can be utilised and more work can be handled.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] At this point you might be asking yourself **'How can you have more than one server listening on the same host and port?
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] When you deploy another server on the same host and port as an existing server it doesn’t actually try and create a new server listening on the same host/port.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] Instead it internally maintains just a single server, and, as incoming connections arrive it distributes them in a round-robin fashion to any of the connect handlers.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] Consequently Vert.x TCP servers can scale over available cores while each instance remains single threaded.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] A client can be configured to automatically retry connecting to the server in the event that it cannot connect.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] This is configured with `setReconnectInterval` and `setReconnectAttempts`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] By default, multiple connection attempts are disabled.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] By default, binary data is logged in hex format.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] You can reduce the data format verbosity to only print the buffer length instead of the entire data by setting the log data fomat.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] Network activity is logged by Netty with the `DEBUG` level and with the `io.netty.handler.logging.LoggingHandler` name.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] You should read the Netty logging section.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] TCP server can be configured with traffic shaping options to enable bandwidth limiting.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] Both inbound and outbound bandwidth can be limited through `TrafficShapingOptions`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] You can set traffic shaping options through `TcpServerConfig`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] These traffic shaping options can also be dynamically updated after server start.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] TCP clients and servers can be configured to use Transport Layer Security - earlier versions of TLS were known as SSL.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] The APIs of the servers and clients are identical whether SSL/TLS is used, and it’s enabled by configuring the `TcpClientConfig` or `TcpServerConfig` instances used to create the servers or clients.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] Server SSL/TLS is enabled with the `TcpServerConfig` `ssl` setting.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] Client SSL/TLS is enabled with the `TcpClientConfig` `ssl` property or `ssl` property.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] The former defines the default client behavior.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] When enabled, the client performs an SSL/TLS handshake with the provided SSL configuration.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] You can also set `ClientSSLOptions` at connect time.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] You can read more about SSL client configuration.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] The client implicitly sends the connecting host as an SNI server name for Fully Qualified Domain Name (FQDN).
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] By default, host verification is **not** configured on the client.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] This verifies the CN portion of the server certificate against the server hostname to avoid Man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] A non SSL/TLS connection can be upgraded to SSL/TLS using `upgradeToSsl`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] You can use the `updateSSLOptions` method to update the key/certifications or trust on a TCP server or client (e.g. to implement certificate rotation).
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] When the update succeeds the new SSL configuration is used, otherwise the previous configuration is preserved.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] The `NetClient` supports either an HTTP/1.x *CONNECT*, *SOCKS4a* or *SOCKS5* proxy.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] The proxy can be configured in the `TcpClientConfig` by setting a `ProxyOptions` object containing proxy type, hostname, port and optionally username and password.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] The DNS resolution is always done on the proxy server, to achieve the functionality of a SOCKS4 client, it is necessary to resolve the DNS address locally.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] You can use `setNonProxyHosts` to configure a list of host bypassing the proxy.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p02] HA PROXY protocol provides a convenient way to safely transport connection information such as a client’s address across multiple layers of NAT or TCP proxies.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] Vert.x allows you to easily write non-blocking QUIC clients and servers.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] The implementation of QUIC relies on Netty and QUICHE, a savoury implementation of QUIC which requires native dependencies depending on OS/platform selection.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] Unlike TCP, QUIC always requires the usage of TLS and thus requires to provide SSL configuration.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] You can read more about SSL server configuration.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] To find out the real port the server is listening on you can use the asynchronous result of `listen`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] When a connection is made the handler will be called with an instance of `QuicConnection`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] A QUIC connection multiplexes QUIC streams which is what your application actually interacts with.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] This is a channel-like interface to the actual connection, and allows you to read and write data as well as do various other things like close the stream.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] To read data from the stream you set the `handler` on the stream.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] You write to a stream using one of `write`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] Instances of `QuicStream` are also `ReadStream` and `WriteStream` instances, so they can be used to pipe data to or from other read and write streams.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] Any side of a stream can cleanly terminate its output, signaling no more data will be emitted.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] You can set an end handler to be notified when the opposite side has terminated its output.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] A stream is closed when output is shut down on both sides.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] Any side of a stream can abruptly terminate the stream, `reset` sends a reset frame signaling no more data will be emitted.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] Reset requires an error code argument used to convey application level error.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] Likewise, `abort` instructs the other side that no more data should be emitted: aborting asks the other side to reset the stream with the provided code.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] You can set an `exceptionHandler` to receive any exceptions that happen on the stream.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] The local address of a `QuicConnection` can be retrieved using `localAddress`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] The remote address, (i.e. the address of the other end of the connection) of a `QuicConnection` can be retrieved using `remoteAddress`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] Shut-down waits until all connections/streams are closed or the shut-down timeout fires.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] When the timeout fires, all resources are forcibly closed.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] Each opened connection and stream is notified with a shutdown event, allowing to perform a protocol level close before the actual close.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] You can close a `server` or `client` to immediately close all open connections/streams and releases all resources.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] If you’re creating QUIC servers and clients from inside verticles, those servers and clients will be automatically closed when the verticle is undeployed.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] QUIC mandates the usage of application layer protocol negotiation (ALPN) and therefore an application protocol should be set with `setApplicationLayerProtocols`, without it, this client will not be capable of handshaking with any server.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] By default, the connection opens a bidirectional stream.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] QUIC supports unidirectional streams too, you can open them as well when the remote side allows it.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] QUIC uses transport parameters to determine the connection behavior, e.g. the maximum number of streams an endpoint allows.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] `QuicConfig` configures transport parameters, you should be aware of a few of them.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] These default parameters model a traditional client / server in which the client opens bidirectional streams like TCP does.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] Each protocol should define proper defaults, e.g.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] HTTP/3 relies on unidirectional streams and therefore configures a few parameters differently for this purpose.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] Vert.x HTTP/3 provides sensitive QUIC transport configuration as well.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] You can configure your endpoint to support the QUIC Datagram Extension.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] Once your endpoint is started, you should check the extension is available.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] QUIC is based on UDP and can be subject to amplification attacks.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] Address validations ensures that a QUIC server cannot be used for such attacks.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] By default, Vert.x performs basic address validation, but this is not sufficient for production.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] We recommend configuring address validation based on cryptographic key instead for production.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] Depending on the nature of the key, either symmetric (MAC) or asymmetric (Digital Signature) is achieved.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] By default, a validation token is valid for 30 seconds, you can configure also configure it.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] You can reduce the data format verbosity to only print the buffer length instead of the entire data by setting the log data format.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] Vert.x QUIC implementation is based on Netty and QUICHE, a savoury implementation of QUIC.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] QUICHE logs in the QLog JSON-SEQ format, QUICHE output is file based.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] It is configured independently of your JVM logging.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] You can use `QLogConfig` to configure QLog.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] The logging granularity is per connection, that is, each connection will be logged in its own file.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] The client performs an SSL/TLS handshake with the client provided SSL configuration.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] You can use the `updateSSLOptions` method to update the key/certifications or trust on a QUIC server or client (e.g. to implement certificate rotation).
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] QUICHE relies on BoringSSL and supports SSL/TLS key logging.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p03] When configured, BoringSSL logs keys for decrypting SSL/TLS in the configured log, which can be then used by tools such as Wireshark to decrypt QUIC traffic.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Vert.x allows you to easily write non-blocking HTTP clients and servers.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Vert.x supports the HTTP/1.0, HTTP/1.1, HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 protocols.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] The base API for HTTP is the same for HTTP/1.x, HTTP/2 and HTTP/3, specific API features are available for dealing with the protocol peculiarities.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Vert.x HTTP servers can be configured to use HTTPS in exactly the same way as TCP or QUIC servers.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Vert.x supports HTTP/1.1 and HTTP/1.0 over plaintext and TLS.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] `Http1ServerConfig` captures the configuration of HTTP/1.x specific aspects.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Vert.x supports HTTP/2 over TLS `h2` and over TCP `h2c`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] The rise of quantum computers will make key exchange protocols such as x25519 obsolete as they will be able to "crack" secret keys quickly.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Vert.x proposes a quantum-safe key exchange protocol, x25519MLKEM768 (official recommendation of NIST) to ensure sessions over TLS are safe against quantum computers.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Hybrid key exchange must be enabled with `setUseHybridKeyExchangeProtocol` and **requires OpenSSL** — it does not work with the JDK SSL engine.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] If OpenSSL is not available at runtime, the TLS handshake will fail rather than silently falling back to a non-quantum-safe key exchange.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] With plain text (TLS is disabled), the server handles `h2c` requests that wants to upgrade connections presenting an HTTP/1.1 upgrade request to HTTP/2.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] It also accepts direct `h2c` (with prior knowledge) connections beginning with the `PRI * HTTP/2.0\r\nSM\r\n` preface.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] `Http2ServerConfig` captures the configuration of HTTP/2 specific aspects.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] When a server accepts an HTTP/2 connection, it sends to the client its `initial settings`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Vert.x supports HTTP/3 over QUIC, we recommend reading the QUIC server section.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] QUIC is new transport layer for HTTP that replaces TCP and has TLS built-in, in fact TLS is mandatory.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] The implementation of QUIC relies on Netty and QUICHE, a savoury implementation of QUIC which requires native dependencies depending on OS/platform selection, you can learn more about running native QUIC.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] `Http3ServerConfig` captures the configuration of HTTP/3 specific aspects.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] QUIC servers can be subject to amplification attacks.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] By default, a server is configured with a basic token validation which works well for development purpose, we recommend configuring token validation based on cryptography instead.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] A server can handle both TCP (HTTP/1.x and HTTP/2) and QUIC (HTTP/3).
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Unless DNS configuration relies on HTTPS resource records to the HTTP/3 endpoint, the recommended way an HTTP server can advertise an HTTP/3 endpoint is to emit an HTTP Alternative Services notification.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] You can pass configuration to `createHttpServer` methods to configure an HTTP server.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] The default host is `0.0.0.0` which means 'listen on all available addresses' and the default port is `80`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] The actual bind is asynchronous so the server might not actually be listening until some time **after** the call to listen has returned.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] When a request arrives, the request handler is called passing in an instance of `HttpServerRequest`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] This object represents the server side HTTP request.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] The handler is called when the headers of the request have been fully read.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] If the request contains a body, that body will arrive at the server some time after the request handler has been called.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] The server request object allows you to retrieve the `uri`, `path`, `params` and `headers`, amongst other things.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Each server request object is associated with one server response object.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] You use `response` to get a reference to the `HttpServerResponse` object.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Here’s a simple example of a server handling a request and replying with "hello world" to it.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Use `method` to retrieve the HTTP method of the request.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] (i.e. whether it’s GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, HEAD, OPTIONS, etc).
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Use `uri` to retrieve the URI of the request.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Note that this is the actual URI as passed in the HTTP request, and it’s almost always a relative URI.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Use `headers` to return the headers of the HTTP request.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] This returns an instance of `MultiMap` - which is like a normal Map or Hash but allows multiple values for the same key - this is because HTTP allows multiple header values with the same key.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Use `authority` to return the authority of the HTTP request.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] For HTTP/1.x requests the `host` header is returned, for HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 requests the `:authority` pseudo header is returned.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Use `params` to return the parameters of the HTTP request.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Just like `headers` this returns an instance of `MultiMap` as there can be more than one parameter with the same name.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Request parameters are sent on the request URI, after the path.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Note that these request parameters are retrieved from the URL of the request.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] If you have form attributes that have been sent as part of the submission of an HTML form submitted in the body of a `multi-part/form-data` request then they will not appear in the params here.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] The address of the sender of the request can be retrieved with `remoteAddress`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] The URI passed in an HTTP request is usually relative.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] The `endHandler` of the request is invoked when the entire request, including any body has been fully read.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Often an HTTP request contains a body that we want to read.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] As previously mentioned the request handler is called when just the headers of the request have arrived so the request object does not have a body at that point.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] This is because the body may be very large (e.g. a file upload) and we don’t generally want to buffer the entire body in memory before handing it to you, as that could cause the server to exhaust available memory.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] To receive the body, you can use the `handler` on the request, this will get called every time a chunk of the request body arrives.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] The object passed into the handler is a `Buffer`, and the handler can be called multiple times as data arrives from the network, depending on the size of the body.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] This is such a common case, that Vert.x provides a `bodyHandler` to do this for you.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] The request object is a `ReadStream` so you can pipe the request body to any `WriteStream` instance.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] See the chapter on streams for a detailed explanation.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] HTML forms can be submitted with either a content type of `application/x-www-form-urlencoded` or `multipart/form-data`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] For url encoded forms, the form attributes are encoded in the url, just like normal query parameters.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] For multi-part forms they are encoded in the request body, and as such are not available until the entire body has been read from the wire.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Multi-part forms can also contain file uploads.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Form attributes have a maximum size of `8192` bytes.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] When the client submits a form with an attribute size greater than this value, the file upload triggers an exception on `HttpServerRequest` exception handler.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] You can set a different maximum size with `setMaxAttributeSize`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Vert.x can also handle file uploads which are encoded in a multi-part request body.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] To receive file uploads you tell Vert.x to expect a multi-part form and set an `uploadHandler` on the request.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] This handler will be called once for every upload that arrives on the server.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] The object passed into the handler is a `HttpServerFileUpload` instance.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] The upload object is a `ReadStream` so you can pipe the request body to any `WriteStream` instance.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] You use `getCookie` to retrieve a cookie by name, or use `cookies` to retrieve all the cookies.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] The set of cookies will be written back in the response automatically when the response headers are written so the browser can store them.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Cookies are described by instances of `Cookie`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] This allows you to retrieve the name, value, domain, path and other normal cookie properties.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Same Site Cookies let servers require that a cookie shouldn’t be sent with cross-site (where Site is defined by the registrable domain) requests, which provides some protection against cross-site request forgery attacks.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] This kind of cookies are enabled using the setter: `setSameSite`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Vert.x can handle compressed body payloads which are encoded by the client with the *deflate*, *gzip*, *snappy* or *brotli* algorithms.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] To enable decompression set `setDecompressionEnabled` on the compression configuration when creating the server.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Snappy is supported without external dependencies.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] When using Gradle, you need to add the runtime native library manually depending on your OS and architecture.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] See the Gradle section of Brotli4j for more details.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 are framed protocol with various frames for the HTTP request/response model.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] The protocol allows other kind of frames to be sent or received.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] To receive custom frames, you can use the `customFrameHandler` on the request, this will get called every time a custom frame arrives.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Custom frames are not subject to flow control - the frame handler will be called immediately when a custom frame is received independently of the streaming state.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] The server response object is an instance of `HttpServerResponse` and is obtained from the request with `response`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] You use the response object to write a response back to the HTTP client.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] The default HTTP status code for a response is `200`, representing `OK`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Use `setStatusCode` to set a different code.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] You can also specify a custom status message with `setStatusMessage`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] If you don’t specify a status message, the default one corresponding to the status code will be used.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] To write data to an HTTP response, you use one of the `write` operations.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] These can be invoked multiple times before the response is ended.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] In this case the string will encoded using UTF-8 and the result written to the wire.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] In this case the string will encoded using the specified encoding and the result written to the wire.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Writing to a response is asynchronous and always returns immediately after write has been queued.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] The first call to write results in the response header being written to the response.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Consequently, if you are not using HTTP chunking then you must set the `Content-Length` header before writing to the response, since it will be too late otherwise.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] If you are using HTTP chunking you do not have to worry.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Once you have finished with the HTTP response you should `end` it.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] With no arguments, the response is simply ended.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] It can also be called with a string or buffer in the same way `write` is called.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] In this case it’s just the same as calling write with a string or buffer followed by calling end with no arguments.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Headers must all be added before any parts of the response body are written.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Vert.x supports HTTP Chunked Transfer Encoding.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] This allows the HTTP response body to be written in chunks, and is normally used when a large response body is being streamed to a client and the total size is not known in advance.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] When in chunked mode, each call to one of the `write` methods will result in a new HTTP chunk being written out.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] When in chunked mode you can also write HTTP response trailers to the response.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] These are actually written in the final chunk of the response.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] To add trailers to the response, add them directly to the `trailers`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] If you were writing a web server, one way to serve a file from disk would be to open it as an `AsyncFile` and pipe it to the HTTP response.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Or you could load it in one go using `readFile` and write it straight to the response.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Alternatively, Vert.x provides a method which allows you to serve a file from disk or the filesystem to an HTTP response in one operation.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Where supported by the underlying operating system this may result in the OS directly transferring bytes from the file to the socket without being copied through user-space at all.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] This is done by using `sendFile`, and is usually more efficient for large files, but may be slower for small files.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] The HTTP response uses the file name extension to set the HTTP response content type header when the file name extension is well known by `MimeMapping` (lookup is case-insensitive).
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Sending a file is asynchronous and may not complete until some time after the call has returned.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] If you want to be notified when the file has been written you can use `sendFile`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Please see the chapter about serving files from the classpath for restrictions about the classpath resolution or disabling it.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] The server response is a `WriteStream` so you can pipe to it from any `ReadStream`, e.g.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] `AsyncFile`, `NetSocket`, `WebSocket` or `HttpServerRequest`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Here’s an example which echoes the request body back in the response for any PUT methods.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] You can also use the `send` method to send a `ReadStream`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Sending a stream is a pipe operation, however as this is a method of `HttpServerResponse`, it will also take care of chunking the response when the `content-length` is not set.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] To send such frames, you can use the `writeCustomFrame` on the response.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] These frames are sent immediately and are not subject to flow control - when such frame is sent there it may be done before other data frames.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] `cancel` is a best effort to cancel a stream by the underlying HTTP protocol.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] You can set an `exceptionHandler` to receive any exceptions that happens before the connection is passed to the `requestHandler` or to the `webSocketHandler`, e.g. during the TLS handshake.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Vert.x will handle invalid HTTP requests and provides a default handler that will handle the common case appropriately, e.g. it does respond with `REQUEST_HEADER_FIELDS_TOO_LARGE` when a request header is too long.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] You can set your own `invalidRequestHandler` to process invalid requests.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Your implementation can handle specific cases and delegate other cases to to `HttpServerRequest.DEFAULT_INVALID_REQUEST_HANDLER`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Vert.x comes with support for HTTP Compression out of the box.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] This means you are able to automatically compress the body of the responses before they are sent back to the client.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] If the client does not support HTTP compression the responses are sent back without compressing the body.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] This allows to handle Client that support HTTP Compression and those that not support it at the same time.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] To enable compression use can configure it with `setCompressionEnabled`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] When HTTP compression is enabled the server will check if the client includes an `Accept-Encoding` header which includes the supported compressions.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] If such a header is found the server will automatically compress the body of the response with one of the supported compressions and send it back to the client.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Be aware that compression may be able to reduce network traffic but is more CPU-intensive.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] To address this latter issue Vert.x allows you to tune the 'compression level' parameter that is native of the gzip/deflate compression algorithms and also set the minimum response content size threshold for compression.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Compression level allows to configure gzip/deflate algorithms in terms of the compression ratio of the resulting data and the computational cost of the compress/decompress operation.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] The compression level is an integer value ranged from '1' to '9', where '1' means lower compression ratio but fastest algorithm and '9' means maximum compression ratio available but a slower algorithm.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] It may not make sense to compress responses under certain size thresholds where the trade-off between CPU and saved network bytes is not beneficial.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] The minimum response content size threshold for compression can be configured via `setContentSizeThreshold`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] For example, if set to '100', responses under 100 bytes will not be compressed.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] By default, it is '0' which means all content can be compressed.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Brotli and zstandard libraries need to be added to your dependencies.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] By default, the client supports HTTP/1, HTTP/2 in plain text.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Vert.x HTTP clients can be configured to use HTTPS in exactly the same way as TCP or QUIC clients.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] `Http1ClientConfig` captures the configuration of HTTP/1.x specific aspects.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] `Http2ClientConfig` captures the configuration of HTTP/2 specific aspects.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Vert.x supports HTTP/3 over QUIC, we recommend reading the QUIC client section.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] `Http3ClientConfig` captures the configuration of HTTP/3 specific aspects.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] A client can mix TCP and QUIC at the same time.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] For performance purpose, the client uses connection pooling when interacting with HTTP servers.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] The concurrency of an HTTP/1.1 server is defined by the client, i.e. the client uses a client defined number of connections to improve performance.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] However, the concurrency of an HTTP/2 or HTTP/3 server is defined by the maximum number of concurrent streams a server allows on a single connection.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] By default, the pool creates up to 5 connections per HTTP/1.1 server and a single connection for other protocols, as recommended.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Normally, you should not need more than a single connection for HTTP/2 or HTTP/3.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] You can pass configuration to `createHttpClient` methods to configure an HTTP client.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] The http client is very flexible and there are various ways you can make requests with it.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] The client will connect to the remote server or reuse an available connection from the client connection pool.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Often you want to make many requests to the same host/port with an http client.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] The headers are an instance of `MultiMap` which provides operations for adding, setting and removing entries.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Http headers allow more than one value for a specific key.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] If you wish to write headers to the request you must do so before any part of the request body is written.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] The `HttpClientRequest` `request` methods connects to the remote server or reuse an existing connection.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] The request instance obtained is pre-populated with some data such like the host or the request URI, but you need to send this request to the server.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] You can call `send` to send a request such as an HTTP `GET` and process the asynchronous `HttpClientResponse`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] You can also send the request with a body.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] `send` with a string, the `Content-Length` header will be set for you if it was not previously set.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] `send` with a buffer, the `Content-Length` header will be set for you if it was not previously set.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] `send` with a stream, if the `Content-Length` header was not previously set, the request is sent with a chunked `Content-Encoding`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] The `send` method send requests at once.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Sometimes you’ll want to have low level control on how you write requests bodies.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] The `HttpClientRequest` can be used to write the request body.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] When you’re writing to a request, the first call to `write` will result in the request headers being written out to the wire.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] The actual write is asynchronous and might not occur until some time after the call has returned.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Non-chunked HTTP requests with a request body require a `Content-Length` header to be provided.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Consequently, if you are not using chunked HTTP then you must set the `Content-Length` header before writing to the request, as it will be too late otherwise.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] If you are calling one of the `end` methods that take a string or buffer then Vert.x will automatically calculate and set the `Content-Length` header before writing the request body.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] If you are using HTTP chunking a `Content-Length` header is not required, so you do not have to calculate the size up-front.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Once you have finished with the HTTP request you must end it with one of the `end` operations.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Ending a request causes any headers to be written, if they have not already been written and the request to be marked as complete.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Or a string or buffer can be provided in the call to `end`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] An `HttpClientRequest` instance is also a `WriteStream` instance.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] You can pipe to it from any `ReadStream` instance.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] Vert.x supports HTTP Chunked Transfer Encoding for requests.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] This allows the HTTP request body to be written in chunks, and is normally used when a large request body is being streamed to the server, whose size is not known in advance.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] You put the HTTP request into chunked mode using `setChunked`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] In chunked mode each call to write will cause a new chunk to be written to the wire.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] In chunked mode there is no need to set the `Content-Length` of the request up-front.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] You can send http form submissions bodies with the `send` variant.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] By default, the form is submitted with the `application/x-www-form-urlencoded` content type header.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p04] If you want to upload files and send attributes, you can create a `ClientMultipartForm` instead.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] A client configured with SSL trust can perform HTTPS request.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] The `setSsl` setting acts as the default client setting.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] SSL can also be enabled/disabled per request with `RequestOptions` or when specifying a scheme with `setAbsoluteURI` method.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] Likewise `setAbsoluteURI` scheme also overrides the default client setting.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] By default, a request use one of the HTTP versions configured by `HttpClientConfig`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] The config versions is an ordered list, the client uses the first version of the list.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] This can be used with a hybrid HTTP client to request an HTTP/3 server: a hybrid client can only determine the IP address for HTTP over TCP using DNS.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] Calling `setFollowAlternativeServices` configures the client to handle alt-svc notifications and use server advertised protocols.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] For instance, `https://google/com` responds to HTTP/1.1 requests with an alternative service for `h3` at same address and port (UDP), subsequent calls to this server can use HTTP/3 instead of HTTP/1.1.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] The client processes alt-svc notifications in the background and tries to connect to the advertised servers before considering them as valid.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] You can set an idle timeout to prevent your application from unresponsive servers using `setIdleTimeout` or `idleTimeout`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] When the request does not return any data within the timeout the request will be `cancelled`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] You can set a connect timeout to prevent your application from unresponsive busy client connection pool.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] The `Future<HttpClientRequest>` is failed when a connection is not obtained before the timeout delay.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] You receive an instance of `HttpClientResponse` into the handler that you specify in of the request methods or by setting a handler directly on the `HttpClientRequest` object.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] You can query the status code and the status message of the response with `statusCode` and `statusMessage`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] The `HttpClientResponse` instance is also a `ReadStream` which means you can pipe it to any `WriteStream` instance.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] The object returned is a `MultiMap` as HTTP headers can contain multiple values for single keys.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] Chunked HTTP responses can also contain trailers - these are sent in the last chunk of the response body.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] The response handler is called when the headers of the response have been read from the wire.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] If the response has a body this might arrive in several pieces some time after the headers have been read.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] We don’t wait for all the body to arrive before calling the response handler as the response could be very large and we might be waiting a long time, or run out of memory for large responses.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] The response `endHandler` is called when the entire response body has been read or immediately after the headers have been read and the response handler has been called if there is no body.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] You can use Vert.x future composition methods to make your code simpler, however the API is event driven, and you need to understand it otherwise you might experience possible data races (i.e. loosing events leading to corrupted data).
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] The client API intentionally does not return a `Future<HttpClientResponse>` because setting a completion handler on the future can be racy when this is set outside the event-loop.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] Confining the `HttpClientRequest` usage within a verticle is the easiest solution as the Verticle will ensure that events are processed sequentially avoiding races.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] When you are interacting with the client possibly outside a verticle then you can safely perform composition as long as you do not delay the response events, e.g. processing directly the response on the event-loop.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] You can also guard the response body with HTTP responses expectations.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] If you need to delay the response processing then you need to `pause` the response or use a `pipe`, this might be necessary when another asynchronous operation is involved.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] As seen above, you must perform sanity checks manually after the response is received.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] You can trade flexibility for clarity and conciseness using *response expectations*.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] `Response expectations` can guard the control flow when the response does not match a criteria.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] As a convenience, the HTTP Client ships a few predicates for common uses cases .
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] Please refer to the `HttpResponseExpectation` documentation for a full list of predefined expectations.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] By default, expectations (including the predefined ones) conveys a simple error message.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] You can retrieve the list of cookies from a response using `cookies`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] Alternatively you can just parse the `Set-Cookie` headers yourself in the response.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] The maximum redirects is `16` by default and can be changed with `setMaxRedirects`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] One size does not fit all and the default redirection policy may not be adapted to your needs.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] The policy handles the original `HttpClientResponse` received and returns either `null` or a `Future<HttpClientRequest>`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] The returned request must be unsent so the original request handlers can be sent and the client can send it after.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] The handler will be called after the HTTP response header is received, the socket will be ready for tunneling and will send and receive buffers.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] `connect` works like `send`, but it reconfigures the transport to exchange raw buffers.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] To receive custom frames, you can use the `customFrameHandler` on the response, this will get called every time a custom frame arrives.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] The http client comes with support for HTTP decompression out of the box.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] This means the client can let the remote http server know that it supports compression, and will be able to handle compressed response bodies.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] An http server is free to either compress with one of the supported compression algorithms or to send the body back without compressing it at all.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] So this is only a hint for the Http server which it may ignore at will.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] To tell the http server which compression algorithm is supported by the client it will include an `Accept-Encoding` header with the supported compression algorithm as value.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] Multiple compression algorithms are supported.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] The server will choose then from one of these.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] You can detect if a server compressed the body by checking for the `Content-Encoding` header in the response sent back from it.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] To enable decompression set `setDecompressionEnabled` on the configuration used when creating the client.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] By default, when the client resolves a hostname to a list of several IP addresses, the client uses the first returned IP address.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] Most load balancing policies are pretty much self-explanatory.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] Hash based routing can be achieved with the `LoadBalancer.CONSISTENT_HASHING` policy.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] The default consistent hashing policy uses 4 virtual nodes per server and uses a random policy in the absence of a routing key.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] Custom load balancing policies can also be used.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] Http keep alive allows http connections to be used for more than one request.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] This can be a more efficient use of connections when you’re making multiple requests to the same server.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] For HTTP/1.x versions, the http client supports pooling of connections, allowing you to reuse connections between requests.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] For pooling to work, keep alive must be true using `setKeepAlive` on the HTTP/1.1 configuration used when configuring the client.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] Vert.x will add a `Connection: Keep-Alive` header to each HTTP/1.0 request sent.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] Vert.x will add a `Connection: Close` header to each HTTP/1.1 request sent to signal that the connection will be closed after completion of the response.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] When making a request with pooling enabled, Vert.x will create a new connection if there are less than the maximum number of connections already created for that server, otherwise it will add the request to a queue.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] Keep alive connections will be closed by the client automatically after a timeout.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] You can set the default timeout using `setKeepAliveTimeout` - any connections not used within this timeout will be closed.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] Please note the timeout value is in seconds not milliseconds.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] The client also supports pipe-lining of requests on a connection.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] Pipe-lining means another request is sent on the same connection before the response from the preceding one has returned.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] Pipe-lining is not appropriate for all requests.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] To enable pipe-lining, it must be enabled using `setPipelining`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] When pipe-lining is enabled requests will be written to connections without waiting for previous responses to return.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] The number of pipe-lined requests over a single connection is limited by `setPipeliningLimit`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] This option defines the maximum number of http requests sent to the server awaiting for a response.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] This limit ensures the fairness of the distribution of the client requests over the connections to the same server.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] Multiplexed HTTP protocols (HTTP/2 and HTTP/3) advocate to use a single connection to a server, by default the http client uses a single connection for each server, all the streams to the same server are multiplexed over the same connection.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] When it is desirable to limit the number of multiplexed streams per connection and use a connection pool instead of a single connection, `setMultiplexingLimit` or `setMultiplexingLimit` can be used.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] The multiplexing limit for a connection is a setting set on the client that limits the number of streams of a single connection.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] The effective value can be even lower if the server sets a lower limit with the `SETTINGS_MAX_CONCURRENT_STREAMS` setting.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] HTTP/2 or HTTP/3 connections will not be closed by the client automatically.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] To close them you can call `close` or close the client instance.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] Alternatively you can set idle timeout using `setIdleTimeout` - any connections not used within this timeout will be closed.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] Please note the idle timeout value is in seconds not milliseconds.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] Most HTTP interactions are performed using `HttpClientAgent` request/response API: the client obtains a connection from its pool of connections to perform a request.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] Alternatively, you can connect directly to a server (bypassing the connection pool) and get an HTTP client connection.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] A client connection can handle a certain amount of concurrent requests.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] When the max number of connection is reached, any subsequent request is queued until a slot is available.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] According to the HTTP 1.1 specification a client can set a header `Expect: 100-Continue` and send the request header before sending the rest of the request body.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] The server can then respond with an interim response status `Status: 100 (Continue)` to signify to the client that it is ok to send the rest of the body.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] The idea here is it allows the server to authorise and accept/reject the request before large amounts of data are sent.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] Sending large amounts of data if the request might not be accepted is a waste of bandwidth and ties up the server in reading data that it will just discard.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] This will be called if the server sends back a `Status: 100 (Continue)` response to signify that it is ok to send the rest of the request.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p05] This is used in conjunction with `writeHead` to write the head of the request.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] On the server side a Vert.x http server can be configured to automatically send back 100 Continue interim responses when it receives an `Expect: 100-Continue` header.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] This is done by setting the option `setHandle100ContinueAutomatically`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] The `HttpConnection` offers an API to deal with HTTP connection events, lifecycle and settings.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] HTTP/1.x implements partially the `HttpConnection` API.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] HTTP/2 implements fully the `HttpConnection` API.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] HTTP/3 implements partially the `HttpConnection` API.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] The Javadoc indicates the level of support for every supported protocol.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] The configuration of multiplexed HTTP connection is configured by the `HttpSettings` object.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] Each endpoint must respect the settings sent by the other side of the connection.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] When a connection is established, the client and the server exchange initial settings.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] HTTP server and client support graceful shutdown.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] Calling `shutdown` initiates the shut-down phase whereby the server or client are given the opportunity to perform clean-up actions.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] When all connections inflight requests are processed, the server or client is then closed.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] In addition, HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 connections send a `GOAWAY` frame to signal the remote endpoint that the connection cannot be used anymore.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] Shutdown waits until all sockets are closed or the shutdown timeout fires.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] Each opened HTTP connections is notified with a shutdown event, allowing to perform cleanup before the actual connection is closed.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] The `closeHandler` notifies when a connection is closed.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] You can share an HTTP client between multiple verticles or instances of the same verticle.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] The first time a shared client is created it will create and return a client.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] Subsequent calls will reuse this client and create a lease to this client.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] The client is closed after all leases have been disposed.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] By default, a client reuses the current event-loop when it needs to create a TCP connection.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] The HTTP client will therefore randomly use event-loops of verticles using it in a safe fashion.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] When several HTTP servers listen on the same port, vert.x orchestrates the request handling using a round-robin strategy.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] This service is listening on the TCP port 8080.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] So, when this verticle is instantiated multiple times as with: `deploymentOptions.setInstances(2)`, what’s happening ?
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] If both verticles bound to the same port, you would receive a socket bind exception.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] Fortunately, Vert.x is handling this case for you.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] When receiving a request it calls the server handlers following a round-robin strategy.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] Let’s now imagine a client calling multiples times the server.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] Consequently, the servers can scale over available cores while each Vert.x verticle instance remains strictly single threaded, and you don’t have to do any special tricks like writing load-balancers in order to scale your server on your multi-core machine.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] You can bind on a shared random ports using a negative port value, the first bind will pick a port randomly, subsequent binds on the same port value will share this random port.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] QUIC server requires to set the `setLoadBalanced` configuration flag prior bind the server.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] QUIC server sharing works differently than TCP, the underlying UDP socket is bound multiple times with the `SO_REUSEPORT` option.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] When the server accepts a QUIC connection, the crafted connection ID encodes information capable of identifying the actual QUIC server assigned to the connection, other servers will forward inbound UDP packets to the connection’s assigned server.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] If you’re creating http servers and clients from inside verticles, those servers and clients will be automatically closed when the verticle is undeployed.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] For debugging purposes, network activity can be logged.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] See network activity logging for TCP / QUIC for detailed explanations.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] Vert.x http servers can be configured to use SNI in exactly the same way as {@linkplain io.vertx.core.net net servers}.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] Vert.x http client will present the actual hostname as *server name* during the TLS handshake.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] Like for TCP servers, you can set traffic shaping options through `getTcpConfig`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] The handler is just notified, the acknowledgement is sent whatsoever.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] Such feature is aimed for implementing protocols on top of HTTP/2.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] An HTTP/2 server is protected against RST flood DDOS attacks (CVE-2023-44487): there is an upper bound to the number of `RST` frames a server can receive in a time window.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] The default configuration sets the upper bound to `200` for a duration of `30` seconds.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] You can use `setRstFloodMaxRstFramePerWindow` and `setRstFloodWindowDuration` to override these settings.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] WebSockets are a web technology that allows a full duplex socket-like connection between HTTP servers and HTTP clients (typically browsers).
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] Vert.x supports WebSockets on both the client and server-side.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] There are two ways of handling WebSockets on the server side.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] The first way involves providing a `webSocketHandler` on the server instance.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] When a WebSocket connection is made to the server, the handler will be called, passing in an instance of `ServerWebSocket`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] By default, the server accepts any inbound WebSocket.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] You can set a WebSocket handshake handler to control the outcome of a WebSocket handshake, i.e. accept or reject an incoming WebSocket.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] You can choose to reject the WebSocket by calling `accept` or `reject`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] The second way of handling WebSockets is to handle the HTTP Upgrade request that was sent from the client, and call `toWebSocket` on the server request.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] The `ServerWebSocket` instance enables you to retrieve the `headers`, `path`, `query` and `URI` of the HTTP request of the WebSocket handshake.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] e Vert.x `WebSocketClient` supports WebSockets.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] By default, the client sets the `origin` header to the server host, e.g http://www.example.com.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] Some servers will refuse such request, you can configure the client to not set this header.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] If the WebSocket message is larger than the maximum WebSocket frame size as configured with `setMaxFrameSize` then Vert.x will split it into multiple WebSocket frames before sending it on the wire.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] A WebSocket message can be composed of multiple frames.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] In this case the first frame is either a *binary* or *text* frame followed by zero or more *continuation* frames.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] The last frame in the message is marked as *final*.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] To send a message consisting of multiple frames you create frames using `WebSocketFrame.binaryFrame` , `WebSocketFrame.textFrame` or `WebSocketFrame.continuationFrame` and write them to the WebSocket using `writeFrame`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] In many cases you just want to send a WebSocket message that consists of a single final frame, so we provide a couple of shortcut methods to do that with `writeFinalBinaryFrame` and `writeFinalTextFrame`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] To read frames from a WebSocket you use the `frameHandler`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] Use `close` to close the WebSocket connection when you have finished with it.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] The `WebSocket` instance is also a `ReadStream` and a `WriteStream` so it can be used with pipes.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] When using a WebSocket as a write stream or a read stream it can only be used with WebSockets connections that are used with binary frames that are no split over multiple frames.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] The `HttpClient` supports accessing HTTP/HTTPS URLs via an HTTP proxy (e.g.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] Squid), a *SOCKS4a*, or a *SOCKS5* proxy.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] The `CONNECT` protocol uses HTTP/1.x but can connect to HTTP/1.x and HTTP/2 servers.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] Connecting to `h2c` (unencrypted HTTP/2 servers) is likely not supported by http proxies since they will support HTTP/1.1 only.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] The proxy can be configured in the `HttpClientConfig` by setting a `ProxyOptions` object containing proxy type, hostname, port and optionally username and password or a prebuilt `Proxy-Authorization` value.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] When the client connects to an HTTP URL, it connects to the proxy server and provides the full URL in the HTTP request, like `GET http://www.somehost.com/path/file.html HTTP/1.1`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] When the client connects to an HTTPS URL, it asks the proxy to create a tunnel to the remote host with the `CONNECT` method.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] By default, a 10 seconds connection timeout is set for the proxy handler in the Vert.x HTTP client.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] The HTTP proxy implementation supports getting ftp:// urls if the proxy supports that.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] `Local maps` allow you to share data safely between different event loops (e.g. different verticles) in the same Vert.x instance.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] In the latter case the key/value will be copied before putting it into the map.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] This way we can ensure there is no *shared access to mutable state* between different threads in your Vert.x application.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] And you won’t have to worry about protecting that state by synchronising access to it.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] `Asynchronous shared maps` allow data to be put in the map and retrieved locally or from any other node.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] This makes them really useful for things like storing session state in a farm of servers hosting a Vert.x Web application.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] Getting the map is asynchronous and the result is returned to you in the handler that you specify.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] When Vert.x is clustered, data that you put into the map is accessible locally as well as on any of the other cluster members.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] You can also remove entries from an asynchronous map, clear them and get the size.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] See the `API docs` for a detailed list of map operations.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] `Asynchronous locks` allow you to obtain exclusive locks locally or across the cluster.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] This is useful when you want to do something or access a resource on only one node of a cluster at any one time.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] Asynchronous locks have an asynchronous API unlike most lock APIs which block the calling thread until the lock is obtained.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] This won’t block, but when the lock is available, the returned future is completed with an instance of `Lock`, signalling that you now own the lock.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] While you own the lock, no other caller, locally or on the cluster, will be able to obtain the lock.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] See the `API docs` for a detailed list of lock operations.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] Sometimes, you use the lock API to retrieve an asynchronous result and apply the acquire/release pattern around the asynchronous call.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] Vert.x provides a simplified lock API to simplify this pattern.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] The lock is acquired before calling the supplier and released when the future returned by the supplier completes.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] It’s often useful to maintain an atomic counter locally or across the different nodes of your application.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] Once you have an instance you can retrieve the current count, atomically increment it, decrement and add a value to it using the various methods.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] See the `API docs` for a detailed list of counter operations.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] The Vert.x `FileSystem` object provides many operations for manipulating the file system.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] There is one file system object per Vert.x instance, and you obtain it with `fileSystem`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] A blocking and a non blocking version of each operation is provided.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] The non blocking versions take a handler which is called when the operation completes or an error occurs.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] The blocking versions are named `xxxBlocking` and return the results or throw exceptions directly.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] Many operations exist to copy, move, truncate, chmod and many other file operations.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] We won’t list them all here, please consult the `API docs` for the full list.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] Vert.x provides an asynchronous file abstraction that allows you to manipulate a file on the file system.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] `AsyncFile` implements `ReadStream` and `WriteStream` so you can *pipe* files to and from other stream objects such as net sockets, http requests and responses, and WebSockets.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] They also allow you to read and write directly to them.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] To use an `AsyncFile` for random access writing you use the `write` method.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] To use an `AsyncFile` for random access reads you use the `read` method.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] When opening an `AsyncFile`, you pass an `OpenOptions` instance.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] These options describe the behavior of the file access.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] For instance, you can configure the file permissions with the `setRead`, `setWrite` and `setPerms` methods.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] You can also configure the behavior if the open file already exists with `setCreateNew` and `setTruncateExisting`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] You can also mark the file to be deleted on close or when the JVM is shutdown with `setDeleteOnClose`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] In the `OpenOptions`, you can enable/disable the automatic synchronisation of the content on every write using `setDsync`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] In that case, you can manually flush any writes from the OS cache by calling the `flush` method.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] This method can also be called with a handler which will be called when the flush is complete.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] `AsyncFile` implements `ReadStream` and `WriteStream`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] You can then use them with a *pipe* to pipe data to and from other read and write streams.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] You can also use the *pipe* to write file content into HTTP responses, or more generally in any `WriteStream`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] When vert.x cannot find the file on the filesystem it tries to resolve the file from the class path.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] Note that classpath resource paths never start with a `/`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] Due to the fact that Java does not offer async access to classpath resources, the file is copied to the filesystem in a worker thread when the classpath resource is accessed the very first time and served from there asynchronously.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] When the same resource is accessed a second time, the file from the filesystem is served directly from the filesystem.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] The original content is served even if the classpath resource changes (e.g. in a development system).
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] This caching behaviour can be set on the `setFileCachingEnabled` option.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] The default value of this option is `true` unless the system property `vertx.disableFileCaching` is defined.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] The path where the files are cached is `/tmp/vertx-cache-UUID` by default and can be customized by setting the system property `vertx.cacheDirBase`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] When using this property, note that it should refer to a directory prefix in a process read/writeable location, for example: `-Dvertx.cacheDirBase=/tmp/my-vertx-cache` (Note that there’s no UUID).
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] Each vert.x process will append it’s own UUID in order to keep caches independently of different applications running on the same machine.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] The whole classpath resolving feature can be disabled system-wide by setting the system property `vertx.disableFileCPResolving` to `true`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] If you want to disable classpath resolving for a particular application but keep it enabled by default system-wide, you can do so via the `setClassPathResolvingEnabled` option.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] To close an `AsyncFile` call the `close` method.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p06] Closing is asynchronous and if you want to be notified when the close has been completed you can specify a handler function as an argument.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Using User Datagram Protocol (UDP) with Vert.x is a piece of cake.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] UDP is a connection-less transport which basically means you have no persistent connection to a remote peer.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Instead, you can send and receive packages and the remote address is contained in each of them.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Beside this UDP is not as safe as TCP to use, which means there are no guarantees that a send Datagram packet will receive it’s endpoint at all.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] The only guarantee is that it will either receive complete or not at all.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Also, you usually can’t send data which is bigger then the MTU size of your network interface, this is because each packet will be send as one packet.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] But, be aware even if the packet size is smaller then the MTU it may still fail.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] At which size it will fail depends on the Operating System etc.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] So rule of thumb is to try to send small packets.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Because of the nature of UDP it is best fit for Applications where you are allowed to drop packets (like for example a monitoring application).
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] The benefits are that it has a lot less overhead compared to TCP, which can be handled by the NetServer and NetClient (see above).
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] To use UDP you first need to create a `DatagramSocket`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] It does not matter here if you only want to send data or send and receive.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] The returned `DatagramSocket` will not be bound to a specific port.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] This is not a problem if you only want to send data (like a client), but more on this in the next section.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] As mentioned before, User Datagram Protocol (UDP) sends data in packets to remote peers but is not connected to them in a persistent fashion.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] This means each packet can be sent to a different remote peer.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] If you want to receive packets you need to bind the `DatagramSocket` by calling `listen(…)` on it.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] This way you will be able to receive DatagramPacket`s that were sent to the address and port on which the `DatagramSocket listens.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Beside this you also want to set a `Handler` which will be called for each received `DatagramPacket`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Be aware that even if the {code AsyncResult} is successed it only means it might be written on the network stack, but gives no guarantee that it ever reached or will reach the remote peer at all.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] If you need such a guarantee then you want to use TCP with some handshaking logic build on top.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Multicast allows multiple sockets to receive the same packets.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] This works by having the sockets join the same multicast group to which you can then send packets.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] We will look at how you can join a Multicast Group and receive packets in the next section.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Sending multicast packets is not different from sending normal Datagram packets.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] The difference is that you pass in a multicast group address to the send method.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] All sockets that have joined the multicast group 230.0.0.1 will receive the packet.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] If you want to receive packets for specific Multicast group you need to bind the `DatagramSocket` by calling `listen(…)` on it to join the Multicast group.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] This way you will receive DatagramPackets that were sent to the address and port on which the `DatagramSocket` listens and also to those sent to the Multicast group.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Beside this you also want to set a Handler which will be called for each received DatagramPacket.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] There are sometimes situations where you want to receive packets for a Multicast group for a limited time.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] In this situations you can first start to listen for them and then later unlisten.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Beside unlisten a Multicast address it’s also possible to just block multicast for a specific sender address.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Be aware this only work on some Operating Systems and kernel versions.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] So please check the Operating System documentation if it’s supported.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] When creating a `DatagramSocket` there are multiple properties you can set to change it’s behaviour with the `DatagramSocketOptions` object.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] You can find out the local address of the socket (i.e. the address of this side of the UDP Socket) by calling `localAddress`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] This will only return an `InetSocketAddress` if you bound the `DatagramSocket` with `listen(…)` before, otherwise it will return null.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] You can close a socket by invoking the `close` method.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Often you will find yourself in situations where you need to obtain DNS informations in an asynchronous fashion.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Unfortunally this is not possible with the API that is shipped with the Java Virtual Machine itself.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Because of this Vert.x offers it’s own API for DNS resolution which is fully asynchronous.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] To obtain a DnsClient instance you will create a new via the Vertx instance.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] You can also create the client with options and configure the query timeout.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Creating the client with no arguments or omitting the server address will use the address of the server used internally for non blocking address resolution.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] A client uses a single event loop for querying purposes, it can safely be used from any thread, including non Vert.x thread.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Try to lookup the A (ipv4) or AAAA (ipv6) record for a given name.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] The first which is returned will be used, so it behaves the same way as you may be used from when using "nslookup" on your operation system.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Try to lookup the A (ipv4) record for a given name.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Try to lookup the AAAA (ipv6) record for a given name.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Try to resolve all A (ipv4) records for a given name.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] This is quite similar to using "dig" on unix like operation systems.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Try to resolve all AAAA (ipv6) records for a given name.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Try to resolve all CNAME records for a given name.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Try to resolve all MX records for a given name.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] The MX records are used to define which Mail-Server accepts emails for a given domain.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Be aware that the List will contain the `MxRecord` sorted by the priority of them, which means MX records with smaller priority coming first in the List.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Try to resolve all TXT records for a given name.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] TXT records are often used to define extra information for a domain.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Try to resolve all NS records for a given name.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] The NS records specify which DNS Server hosts the DNS informations for a given domain.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Try to resolve all SRV records for a given name.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] The SRV records are used to define extra information like port and hostname of services.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Some protocols need this extra information.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Be aware that the List will contain the SrvRecords sorted by the priority of them, which means SrvRecords with smaller priority coming first in the List.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Please refer to the API docs for the exact details.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Try to resolve the PTR record for a given name.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] The PTR record maps an ipaddress to a name.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Try to do a reverse lookup for an ipaddress.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] This is basically the same as resolve a PTR record, but allows you to just pass in the ipaddress and not a valid PTR query string.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] As you saw in previous sections the DnsClient allows you to pass in a Handler which will be notified with an AsyncResult once the query was complete.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] In case of an error it will be notified with a DnsException which will hole a `DnsResponseCode` that indicate why the resolution failed.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] This DnsResponseCode can be used to inspect the cause in more detail.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] All of those errors are "generated" by the DNS Server itself.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Use virtual threads to write Vert.x code that looks like it is synchronous.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] You still write the traditional Vert.x code processing events, but you have the opportunity to write synchronous code for complex workflows and use thread locals in such workflows.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] The non-blocking nature of Vert.x leads to asynchronous APIs.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Asynchronous APIs can take various forms including callback style, promises and reactive extensions.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] In some cases, programming using asynchronous APIs can be more challenging than using a direct synchronous style, in particular if you have several operations that you want to do sequentially.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Also, error propagation is often more complex when using asynchronous APIs.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Virtual thread support allows you to work with asynchronous APIs, but using a direct synchronous style that you’re already familiar with.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] It does this by using Java 21 virtual threads.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Virtual threads are very lightweight threads that do not correspond to underlying kernel threads.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] When they are blocked they do not block a kernel thread.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] You can deploy virtual thread verticles.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] A virtual thread verticle is capable of awaiting Vert.x futures and gets the result synchronously.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] When the verticle **awaits** a result, the verticle can still process events like an event-loop verticle.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] You can use `await` to suspend the current virtual thread until the awaited result is available.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] The virtual thread is effectively blocked, but the application can still process events.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] When a virtual thread awaits for a result and the verticle needs to process a task, a new virtual thread is created to handle this task.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] When the result is available, the virtual thread execution is resumed and scheduled after the current task is suspended or finished.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] A virtual thread verticle can interact safely with fields before an `await` call.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] However, if you are reading a field before an `await` call and reusing the value after the call, you should keep in mind that this value might have changed.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] You should read/write fields before calling `await` to avoid this.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] When your application blocks without using `await`, e.g. using `ReentrantLock#lock`, the Vert.x scheduler is not aware of it and cannot schedule events on the verticle: it behaves like a worker verticle, yet using virtual threads.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] This use case is not encouraged yet not forbidden, however the verticle should be deployed with several instances to deliver the desired concurrency, like a worker verticle.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Thread locals are only reliable within the execution of a context task.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] There are several objects in Vert.x that allow items to be read from and written.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] In Vert.x, write calls return immediately, and writes are queued internally.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] It’s not hard to see that if you write to an object faster than it can actually write the data to its underlying resource, then the write queue can grow unbounded - eventually resulting in memory exhaustion.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] To solve this problem a simple flow control (*back-pressure*) capability is provided by some objects in the Vert.x API.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Any flow control aware object that can be *written-to* implements `WriteStream`, while any flow control object that can be *read-from* is said to implement `ReadStream`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Let’s take an example where we want to read from a `ReadStream` then write the data to a `WriteStream`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] A very simple example would be reading data from a `NetSocket` then writing it to an `AsyncFile`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] There is a problem with the example above: if data is read from the socket faster than it can be written to the file, it will build up in the write queue of the `AsyncFile`, eventually running out of RAM.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] This might happen, for example, if the actual file is stored on a slow network file system, effectively putting back-pressure on the connection.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] This example won’t run out of RAM, but we’ll end up losing data if the write queue gets full.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] The `drainHandler` event handler will get called when the write queue is ready to accept more data, this resumes the `NetSocket` that allows more data to be read.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] This use case is quite common while writing Vert.x applications, so we added the `pipeTo` method that does all of this hard work for you.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] This does exactly the same thing as the more verbose example, plus it handles stream failures and termination: the destination `WriteStream` is ended when the pipe completes with success or a failure.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] When the pipe is closed, the streams handlers are unset and the `ReadStream` resumed.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] `ReadStream` is implemented by `HttpClientResponse`, `DatagramSocket`, `HttpClientRequest`, `HttpServerFileUpload`, `HttpServerRequest`, `MessageConsumer`, `NetSocket`, `WebSocket` and `AsyncFile`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] When a hot read stream is obtained (e.g.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] `HttpServerRequest`), the read stream is in flowing mode, when a cold read stream is obtained (e.g.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] `AsyncFile`), the read stream is in fetch mode with no demand.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] `WriteStream` is implemented by `HttpClientRequest`, `HttpServerResponse` `WebSocket`, `NetSocket` and `AsyncFile`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Java collectors can reduce a `ReadStream` to a result in a similar fashion `java.util.Stream` does, yet in an asynchronous fashion.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Note that `collect` overrides any previously handler set on the stream.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] The record parser allows you to easily parse protocols which are delimited by a sequence of bytes, or fixed size records.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] It transforms a sequence of input buffer to a sequence of buffer structured as configured (either fixed size or separated records).
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] For more details, check out the `RecordParser` class.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] You can easily parse JSON structures but that requires to provide the JSON content at once, but it may not be convenient when you need to parse very large structures.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] The non-blocking JSON parser is an event driven parser able to deal with very large structures.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] It transforms a sequence of input buffer to a sequence of JSON parse events.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] The parser is non-blocking and emitted events are driven by the input buffers.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Event driven parsing provides more control but comes at the price of dealing with fine grained events, which can be inconvenient sometimes.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] The value mode can be set and unset during the parsing allowing you to switch between fine grained events or JSON object value events.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] For more details, check out the `JsonParser` class.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Most Vert.x objects are safe to access from different threads.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] *However* performance is optimised when they are accessed from the same context they were created from.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] For example if you have deployed a verticle which creates a `NetServer` which provides `NetSocket` instances in it’s handler, then it’s best to always access that socket instance from the event loop of the verticle.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] If you stick to the standard Vert.x verticle deployment model and avoid sharing objects between verticles then this should be the case without you having to think about it.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] In a perfect world, there will be no war or hunger, all APIs will be written asynchronously and bunny rabbits will skip hand-in-hand with baby lambs across sunny green meadows.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Fact is, many, if not most libraries, especially in the JVM ecosystem have synchronous APIs and many of the methods are likely to block.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] A good example is the JDBC API - it’s inherently synchronous, and no matter how hard it tries, Vert.x cannot sprinkle magic pixie dust on it to make it asynchronous.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] We’re not going to rewrite everything to be asynchronous overnight so we need to provide you a way to use "traditional" blocking APIs safely within a Vert.x application.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] As discussed before, you can’t call blocking operations directly from an event loop, as that would prevent it from doing any other useful work.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] It’s done by calling `executeBlocking` with blocking code to execute, as return you get a future completed with the result of the blocking code execution.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] By default, if executeBlocking is called several times from the same context (e.g. the same verticle instance) then the different executeBlocking are executed *serially* (i.e. one after another).
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] If you don’t care about ordering you can call `executeBlocking` specifying `false` as the argument to `ordered`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] In this case any executeBlocking may be executed in parallel on the worker pool.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] A worker verticle is always executed with a thread from the worker pool.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] By default blocking code is executed on the Vert.x worker pool, configured with `setWorkerPoolSize`.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] When several workers are created with the same name, they will share the same pool.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] The worker pool is destroyed when all the worker executors using it are closed.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] When an executor is created in a Verticle, Vert.x will close it automatically for you when the Verticle is undeployed.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] A Vert.x instance has a few extension points knows as *SPI* (Service Provider Interface).
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Such SPI are often loaded from the classpath using Java’s `ServiceLoader` mechanism.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] By default, Vert.x does not record any metrics nor does any tracing.
[src:vertx/vertx-core-java-p07] Instead, it provides an SPI for others to implement which can be added to the classpath.
